<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> British Plant Nuke Processing Cited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A Rolls-Royce plant in central England has been  
processing nuclear fuel for the Defense Ministry without the local 
community's knowledge, and it had no public emergency plan in case 
of an accident, The Sunday Times reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The people of Derby had been aware that the factory makes  
engines for Trident nuclear submarines, but not that nuclear fuel 
was processed because the work is classified, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is very worrying, especially after what has happened in  
Japan. We need to know what is happening,'' said Alison Jones, a 
mother of two from nearby Allenton. 
</P>
<P>
	Another resident, who declined to give his name, said: ``I think  
it's disgraceful. It is very worrying for people who live nearby.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The anti-nuclear organization Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament  
said it had been contacted by workers at the Rolls-Royce plant 
after last month's nuclear accident at a Japanese plant because 
they feared a similar foul-up. Sixty-nine people were exposed to 
radiation Sept. 30 at Tokaimura in Japan's worst-ever nuclear 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
	CND called Sunday for the plant to be closed down immediately.  
</P>
<P>
	A Defense Ministry spokesman confirmed late Saturday that the  
department delivers fuel to the civilian plant, where it is treated 
for use in nuclear submarine reactors. The plant is licensed by 
Britain's Nuclear Installations Inspectorate and has full 
processing approval, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, a report by the inspectorate criticized the plant's  
safety procedures. But the plant subsequently changed its 
procedures and practiced the new ones, and government officials 
said they are now satisfied. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary Geoff Hoon rejected calls for the plant to be  
closed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those concerns have been addressed by the Nuclear  
Installations Inspectorate and they've given the plant an entirely 
clean bill of health,'' he told SKY News. ``Those concerns have 
been thoroughly investigated.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
