<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Considers Republic Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) -- Australia's republicans launched  
their official campaign Sunday for the country to drop Britain's 
Queen Elizabeth II as head of state, warning that if voters don't 
do it now they won't get another chance for decades. 
</P>
<P>
	In a referendum scheduled for Nov. 6, some 11 million voters  
will decide whether they want the constitution changed to make 
Australia a republic with its own elected head of state. Australia, 
along with other Commonwealth countries such as Canada and Papua 
New Guinea, still recognizes Elizabeth II as the head of state. 
</P>
<P>
	Launching the ``yes'' campaign Sunday, Australian Republican  
Movement chairman Malcolm Turnbull said impetus for changing the 
constitution would be lost if the November referendum isn't passed. 
</P>
<P>
	``This referendum is the best chance in our lifetimes to have an  
Australian republic,'' Turnbull said. ``If it fails, the next 
republican proposal will take many years, maybe decades, to be 
formulated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney-general Daryl Williams said the constitutional changes  
would not alter Australia's system of government. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will continue to have a stable democracy under (the  
republican) model,'' Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	But leading monarchists said changing Australia's head of state  
would create confusion overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really think we should be mucking about with our  
constitution at a time of very great instability in our own region 
and around the world,'' Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said 
Sunday at a separate, pro-monarchy function. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
