<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Oct. 17, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	N.C. Readies For Another Hurricane  
</P>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, N.C. (AP) -- A hurricane warning is in effect from  
Savannah, Ga., to Cape Hatteras, N.C. as Hurricane Irene continues 
to track toward North Carolina. Topsail Beach northeast of 
Wilmington was ordered evacuated this morning. Nearby Onslow Beach, 
under the Marine Corps' jurisdiction, was closed as well. Earlier 
this morning, the center of the storm was about 115 miles south of 
Charleston, S.C., moving north at 10 mph. Projections put the 
ragged eye of the storm near Cape Romain, just northeast of 
Charleston, by this afternoon. 

</P>
<P>
	New Pakistan Regime Targets Economy  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Nearly a week after overthrowing  
Pakistan's civilian government, coup leader Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf 
is to make a televised speech this evening to outline his plans for 
a transitional government. Musharraf canceled plans to make the 
speech yesterday. The top priority of this transitional government, 
said an army statement, will be ``economic revival'' in this poor 
nation of 140 million people, most of whom can neither read nor 
write. The average annual income in Pakistan is $800, according to 
U.N. figures. 

</P>
<P>
	Gaza Strip Passage May be Delayed  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- The opening of a land link between the West  
Bank and Gaza Strip has been delayed for the second time in two 
weeks because of disagreements over how to operate it, Palestinian 
and Israeli officials said. The so-called safe passage was to have 
opened today, allowing Palestinians to move relatively freely for 
the first time between the two Palestinian areas, which lie on 
either side of Israel. But the Israelis and Palestinians were 
unable to agree yesterday on where in the Gaza Strip to place a 
joint office that would issue travel permits to Palestinians. 

</P>
<P>
	Beijing Police Detain Dissident  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- A veteran Chinese dissident who was released  
earlier this year after serving nearly 10 years in prison has been 
taken away by police in Beijing, a rights group said today. Sun 
Weibang was visiting the wife of imprisoned activist Xu Wenli on 
Friday when police took him into custody, according to the Hong 
Kong-based Information Center of Human Rights and Democratic 
Movement in China. Sun's whereabouts are unknown and his family 
fear he will be sent back to prison, the Information Center said. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Backs Racial Diversity Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Of all the challenges the United States will  
face in the next century, by far the most important is building 
``one America out of this crazy quilt of all of us who live here,'' 
President Clinton told an Italian-American audience last night. 
Solve the problem of prejudice and group hatred, he said, ``and 
we'll find a way to deal with all the rest of our problems.'' 
Clinton addressed the 24th annual black-tie dinner of the National 
Italian American Foundation, the major Washington advocate for 
nearly 15 million Italian Americans, the nation's fifth largest 
ethnic group. 

</P>
<P>
	47 Injured on Hong Kong-Bound Jet  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- A China Southern Airlines jet ran into strong  
turbulence and plunged 2,000 feet shortly before it landed in Hong 
Kong today, injuring 47 passengers, seven of them seriously. The 
seven include one American and one Japanese, said Dr. N. K. Leung, 
chief executive of the government-run Princess Margaret Hospital. 
The plane fell from 21,000 feet to 19,000 feet in about five to 10 
seconds. Some of the passengers were not wearing seat belts, and 
airport officials said there had been no prior announcement to put 
them on before the jolt. 

</P>
<P>
	Few Blacks in S. African Boardrooms  
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Whites still dominate South  
African company boardrooms five years after the end of apartheid, 
according to a study released today. Blacks made up 12 percent of 
the directors of South African companies listed on the stock 
exchange, according to the Sunday Times of Johannesburg, which 
commissioned the private study. Even among black empowerment 
companies that were intended to redress racial imbalance in the 
control of wealth, only 37 percent of 260 directors in such 
organizations are black, the study said. 

</P>
<P>
	Hakkinen Wins Formula One Title  
</P>
<P>
	SEPANG, Malaysia (AP) -- Mika Hakkinen was declared the winner of  
the Malaysian Grand Prix today and captured the Formula One 
drivers' title after the top two Ferraris were disqualified. 
Ferrari teammates Eddie Irvine and Michael Schumacher crossed the 
finish line first and second. But more than three hours after the 
race -- following their awards and interviews -- they were 
disqualified for technical violations. Ferrari appealed and a 
ruling is expected tomorrow at the Swiss headquarters of the 
International Automobile Federation. If Ferrari loses, Hakkinen 
wins the world title for the second straight year. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
