<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 21:03:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  47 Injured on Hong Kong-Bound Jet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- A China Southern Airlines jet ran into strong  
turbulence and plunged 2,000 feet shortly before it landed in Hong 
Kong on Sunday. Forty-seven passengers were injured, seven of them 
seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight people remained hospitalized late Sunday. The seven who  
were seriously hurt included one American and one Japanese, said 
Dr. N. K. Leung, chief executive of the government-run Princess 
Margaret Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane fell from 21,000 feet to 19,000 feet in about five to  
10 seconds, said Wang Guixiang, president and director of China's 
National Civil Aviation Corporation. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the passengers were not wearing seat belts, and airport  
officials said there had been no prior announcement to put them on 
before the jolt. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Au-yeung, a Hong Kong tour guide, said there was no  
warning from the crew before the plane suddenly plunged. Then there 
was an announcement by a crew member asking if there were any 
doctors aboard, he recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw about 10 people in front of me who flew off their seats  
and hit the roof of the cabin,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ambulances rushed the injured to three hospitals after the  
Boeing 757, with 160 passengers aboard, arrived at Chek Lap Kok 
airport from the southern Chinese city of Kunming, authorities 
said. About 10 people had to be carried off the plane on 
stretchers. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescue efforts were delayed because the pilot failed to inform  
air traffic controllers of the incident, said Alex Au, Hong Kong's 
acting director of civil aviation. And even after he landed the 
plane, the pilot informed only his company, which later relayed the 
message to airport authorities, Au said. 
</P>
<P>
	Medical teams who arrived at the scene were surprised to find  
that dozens were injured after the pilot, whose name was not 
disclosed, had said only six were hurt, said airport fire officer 
Lau Chi-ho. 
</P>
<P>
	Southern Airlines officials were not immediately available for  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	In August, three people were killed when an MD-11 jet belonging  
to Taiwan's China Airlines crashed while landing in a storm at the 
airport. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
