<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.H. Gov. Delays Gore Endorsement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore is putting off a  
trip to New Hampshire to give the state's governor time to deal 
with an education funding crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Jeanne Shaheen had planned to formally endorse Gore for the  
Democratic presidential nomination Monday, but said Sunday night 
that the state's education problem needed her full attention. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Supreme Court ruled Friday that a statewide property  
tax enacted to help fund education is unconstitutional, leaving the 
state with the obligation of paying $825 million toward local 
school costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore campaign official Toby Chaudhuri said the vice president  
was postponing his visit. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaheen, in a statement, said, ``Al Gore has my strongest  
support and I look forward to holding an official endorsement event 
with him in the future, and campaigning hard for him during the 
next few months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The endorsement has been widely expected. Shaheen's husband,  
William Shaheen, is director of Gore's New Hampshire campaign. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
