<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Injury Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	It was a rough day for NFL quarterbacks. Fortunately for Dan  
Marino, Mark Brunell and Charlie Batch, they had worthy backups to 
lead their teams to victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Marino became the first quarterback in NFL history to pass for  
60,000 yards with his only completion, then left because of a 
shoulder injury after two series against the New England Patriots 
on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Marino, who complained of an injured right shoulder during the  
week, completed his first pass for 8 yards to run his career total 
to 60,001. 
</P>
<P>
	But on his second throw he fumbled, and Patriots linebacker Andy  
Katzenmoyer returned it 57 yards for a touchdown. On the next 
series, Marino tried a short pass that fell well short of the 
intended receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I might be able to start,'' said Marino, who will  
have an MRI on Monday. ``But when I warmed up, I was throwing 
changeups. Usually I throw fastballs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Damon Huard entered on the third series, and his first pass was  
intercepted for a TD by New England's Ty Law, who returned the ball 
27 yards for a TD. But Huard went on to lead the Dolphins to a 
31-30 win. 
</P>
<P>
	Brunell left Jacksonville's 24-7 victory over Cleveland in the  
third quarter with bruised ribs. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Tom Coughlin said Brunell took the first blow to the ribs  
sometime in the first half, then was knocked out of the game when 
he strained the ribs making a long throw down the sideline to start 
the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Brunell returned to the sideline and threw for a brief period,  
but Coughlin said there was no way the quarterback would return to 
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had difficulty twisting and turning and throwing the  
ball,'' Coughlin said. ``So we made the decision not to put him 
in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Backup Jay Fiedler led three scoring drives and finished  
12-for-14 for 113 yards and one touchdown for the Jags. 
</P>
<P>
	Batch bruised his right arm and did not return for the start of  
second half of the Lions' game with the Minnesota Vikings. 
</P>
<P>
	Gus Frerotte started the second half with Detroit leading 19-0,  
and the Vikings rallied to take the lead, but the Lions won 25-23 
on Jason Hanson's sixth field goal, a 48-yarder with 7 seconds 
left. 
</P>
<P>
	Frerotte completed five straight passes on the game-winning  
drive. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona QB Jake Plummer left Sunday night's game against the  
Washington Redskins early in the third quarter when he broke the 
ring finger on his right hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Plummer, knocked out of a game for the second time in as many  
weeks, was sacked by linebacker Shawn Barber early in the third 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Plummer's finger became stuck in Barber's facemask on the hit.  
He went to the locker room for X-rays and came back with his hand 
wrapped. 
</P>
<P>
	Plummer, who threw two interceptions, including one by Champ  
Bailey for a touchdown, already was bothered by a hip pointer that 
sidelined him for much of last week's 14-3 victory over the New 
York Giants. Plummer missed most of the preseason with a sprained 
right thumb. 
</P>
<P>
	New York Jets quarterback Ray Lucas, a replacement for  
ineffective starter Rick Mirer, sprained his left ankle when he was 
sacked on the final play of a 16-13 loss to Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Moulds, Buffalo's leading receiver, injured his hamstring  
with about 7 minutes left in a 20-14 loss to Oakland and will be 
out 3-4 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Three prominent players were injured in Pittsburgh's 17-3  
victory over Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals' Corey Dillon missed much of the first half with a  
twisted ankle and was held to 78 yards rushing. Darnay Scott left 
with bruised ribs after his first catch. 
</P>
<P>
	For the Steelers, Pro Bowl center Dermontti Dawson was lost to a  
pulled hamstring on their third possession. Dawson said he's been 
bothered by the injury for two weeks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
