<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Says It Will Win Beef Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Foreign Secretary Robin Cook insisted Sunday that  
France ``cannot sustain'' its refusal to allow British beef into 
the country in defiance of the European Union and predicted Britain 
would win the day if the dispute goes to court. 
</P>
<P>
	The 15-nation EU ruled in August that beef from Britain was safe  
again for international sale after the scare over the illness 
commonly known as ``mad cow disease.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But on Oct. 1 France said it would continue to ban the imports,  
based on a recommendation from the French food safety committee. 
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said Saturday that France would 
lift the ban only if its own scientific evidence proves it no 
longer poses health risks. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are in the wrong. They cannot sustain this position,''  
Cook told the British Broadcasting Corp. ``Ultimately if it goes to 
court they will lose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The sooner they recognize this and the sooner they accept the  
binding agreement (on European Union members), the better,'' he 
said, adding that the French report produced no new scientific 
evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``The decision of the European committee on this is expected in  
less than a couple of weeks and after that we expect the Commission 
to take action,'' Cook said. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Commission is the watchdog of the EU treaty which  
bans unfair trade practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, in Paris, French Agriculture Minister Jean Glavany  
was quoted in Le Parisien newspaper Sunday defending France's 
position. 
</P>
<P>
	``(The EU) gave us an ultimatum two weeks ago to lift the  
embargo by Oct. 7. Then until Oct. 14, and then, until Oct. 25 at 
the earliest. They understood that the scientists needed to 
speak,'' he said. ``The French have been heard ... It seems that no 
scientist could risk saying that there is absolutely no danger in 
eating British beef.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
