<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 17:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> America's Cup Yachts Take to the Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) -- After years in planning rooms and  
laboratories, after months of practice and intrigue, the America's 
Cup yachts finally took to the open seas Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The starter's gun boomed across New Zealand's Hauraki Gulf at  
10:40 a.m. to begin the Louis Vuitton Cup challenger series, a 
regatta that will last four months and feature 11 yachts. 
</P>
<P>
	In perfect spring conditions, the New York Yacht Club's Young  
America beat America True by 37 seconds; Japan's Nippon beat 
Hawaii's Abracadabra 2000 by 38 seconds; Italy's Prada beat the 
Swiss FAST2000 by 4:20; Dennis Conner's Stars and Stripes beat Le 
Defi Francais by 9 seconds; and AmericaOne beat the Spanish 
challenge by 1:09. Young Australia had the bye. 
</P>
<P>
	The afternoon pairings had Prada vs. Nippon; Spanish Challenge  
vs. Young America; America True vs. AmericaOne; Young Australia vs. 
Le Defi Francais; and Abracadabra vs. Fast2000. Stars and Stripes 
had the bye. 
</P>
<P>
	In each of three round-robins in the challenger series between  
Oct. 18 and Dec. 12, each team will race all other teams. A boat 
gets one point for each win in the first round robin, four points 
in the second, nine in the third. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 700 races will have been run to decide the challenger.  
</P>
<P>
	The best six teams will compete in semifinals in January, and  
the winner and Team New Zealand will meet in a best-of-9 series in 
February for the America's Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Team New Zealand, using only two boats to prepare for its  
defense, has its own course on which to practice. 
</P>
<P>
	This is only the second time the America's Cup has been held  
outside the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	New Zealand, a South Pacific island nation of some 3.5 million  
people, features volcanic mountain landscapes plunging into a 
rugged coastline. It claims to have the highest per-capita boat 
ownership of any country and calls Auckland its City of Sails. 
</P>
<P>
	When the 24-inch high silver trophy was paraded through Auckland  
last week, tens of thousands of cheering people lined the streets. 
</P>
<P>
	The trophy was shown in a bulletproof case because of a  
sledgehammer attack by a political activist in 1997. The trophy had 
to be returned to its maker for repairs. 
</P>
<P>
	For many teams, preparations began the moment Sir Peter Blake's  
Black Magic trounced Conner's Stars and Stripes in a 5-0 victory 
off San Diego in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	With cutting-edge technology as important as skilled sailors,  
team budgets are among the most expensive in the competition's 
148-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest spenders are among the favorites, including the New  
York Yacht Club, which held the trophy for 132 years until 1983. 
The NYYC launched a $40 million campaign for its boat Young 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	Tough competition is expected from AmericaOne, the $32 million  
bid from the St. Francis Yacht Club; the Prada challenge from 
Italy, which at $50 million has the largest budget; and Japan's 
Nippon, which will spend $20 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Other teams include Conner, a four-time winner and two-time  
loser of the cup, and two other U.S. syndicates, including 
America's True, which has the only woman skipper in Dawn Riley. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
