<DOCNO> APW19991017.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 15:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Has Mixed Reaction to Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States on Sunday praised Gen.  
Pervaiz Musharraf for pledging to return Pakistan to democratic 
rule but expressed disappointment that the military leader offered 
no timetable for that transition. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials said they were pleased by several points  
Musharraf made in an address Sunday, his first public appearance 
since announcing last week that he had ousted Pakistan's civilian 
government. They cited his references to reducing the military 
presence at the border with India. 
</P>
<P>
	But they also said they were concerned that Musharraf left open  
the question of when democracy will return to Pakistan and urged 
him to do so as quickly as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	``As General Musharraf told his nation, actions speak louder  
than words,'' State Department spokesman James Rubin said. ``Our 
own actions toward Pakistan in the days ahead will be guided by the 
steps taken by the new authorities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, speaking a short time  
before Musharraf's address, told CNN's ``Late Edition'' that the 
United States specifically is looking to see how Musharraf handles 
civil liberties, press freedoms and human rights issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're saying here is that the people of Pakistan should  
have the right to have a democratic or a constitutional government, 
that they also need to be able to be a part of the international 
system economically, that they should not have corruption there, 
that they need to have their civil liberties,'' Albright said. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the deposed Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, the Clinton  
administration is not pressing for his return to power, Albright 
acknowledged, but added, ``We believe that it's important that his 
security be guaranteed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In recent days, U.S. military leaders have made it clear that  
they were not alarmed by the military takeover, and that they 
consider Musharraf pro-Western and capable of controlling the 
country's nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, the military coup prompted the White House to  
announce it will impose new sanctions against Pakistan. State 
Department officials said a $1.7 million health program, operated 
by private organizations, would be suspended. But a $2.5 million 
program to counter narcotics would not be interrupted. 
</P>
<P>
	William Milam, the U.S. ambassador to Pakistan, met with  
Musharraf for two hours Friday in Islamabad to press for assurances 
on a transition to civilian rule. At the time, Musharraf did not 
reveal his intentions, the White House said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. military leaders have not had close contact with the  
Pakistani military in recent years because of extensive U.S. 
sanctions imposed in 1990 by the Bush administration and additional 
restrictions that followed Pakistan's nuclear tests in 1998. But 
military relations were close during the Cold War. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday, Musharraf said he wanted good relations with the United  
States but that Pakistan's foreign policy would be more oriented 
toward relations with the Muslim world. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said U.S. officials were encouraging Musharraf to take  
``confidence-building measures that could lead to a lessening of 
tensions with India,'' and that they hope Musharraf would also thin 
out troops along the line of control in Kashmir. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because we do not believe military takeovers are the  
appropriate method for resolving the problems that face 
democracies, we welcome ... his promise that the armed forces would 
not stay in charge any longer than necessary,'' Rubin said. ``At 
the same time, we are disappointed that he did not offer a clear 
timetable for the early restoration of constitutional, civilian and 
democratic government. We call upon him to do so now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Musharraf listed seven objectives of his administration:  
rebuilding national confidence, easing tensions between the 
provinces, reviving the economy and restoring investor confidence, 
strengthening law and order, removing politics from state 
institutions, giving more power to the people, and ensuring a quick 
recovery of illicit wealth. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
