<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Displaced N.C. Families Moved Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. (AP) -- Fannie Lewis was in a shelter again  
Sunday after Hurricane Irene forced her from the government camper 
where she had begun to make a new life after Hurricane Floyd 
destroyed her home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I fear the next step we're going to make is in the ground,''  
the 37-year-old Lewis said glumly as heavy rain drummed on a 
corrugated plastic roof over the walkway at D.S. Johnson School. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis and about 300 other refugees from Princeville, Tarboro and  
Rocky Mount had only weeks ago moved into campers in an industrial 
park after Floyd's floodwaters destroyed their homes and forced 
them into shelters. This weekend, they were evacuated from the 
campers, which are not designed to withstand strong winds, and 
moved back into shelters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm getting to the point where I can't take it any more,''  
said Herbert Person Jr., 48, who lost his Princeville home, which 
was nearly paid for. He was living in one of the trailers, eating 
donated food, when he became a refugee again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've worked hard all my life and paid taxes, and now I feel  
like I have nothing,'' he said. ``I can't work because I have to 
take care of business. But if I don't work, I'm afraid the bank 
will take my truck. I'm so stressed out I don't know what to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Put this on the front page of the newspaper -- we need money!''  
he said, drawing a cheer from the largely male crowd outside the 
shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	Haywood Sherrod, 50, who suffers from high blood pressure and  
diabetes, said he left his medication back in his camper. 
</P>
<P>
	``They came by around 6:30 p.m. last night and told us we had to  
leave because they were concerned about the high winds,'' he said. 
``I just said, `Oh, no. Not again.' It's hard to run again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a long time before the people around here can  
get Floyd out of our minds,'' he said, shaping a piece of cardboard 
from a discarded box to fit inside one of his slippers to keep his 
sore feet dry and warm. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearby, evacuees lined up for a lunch of chicken, french fries  
and soft drinks. They ignored the tiny stools and tables as they 
ate the hot food. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like a prisoner,'' said Christine Crews, 25, as she  
waited her turn with her mother, Barbara Crews, 48. ``I was forced 
to run from my home, then they put me in a trailer. We were just 
starting to settle in. Then they knock on my door and tell me I 
have to run again.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
