<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Details of GM Concept Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The nine concept vehicles that General Motors Corp. will unveil  
at auto shows in the next several months: 
</P>
<P>
	SATURN CV1: The first concept vehicle from Saturn is a small,  
all-wheel drive sport utility vehicle with rear doors that fold 
open. 
</P>
<P>
	OLDSMOBILE PROFILE: A four-door hatchback with a supercharged  
V-6, the Profile is filled with gadgetry -- voice-activated 
controls, satellite navigation and e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	BUICK LACROSSE: The LaCrosse starts out as a big, V-8 powered  
sedan. But hidden under motorized panels in the rear is a small 
pickup bed. 
</P>
<P>
	GMC TERRADYNE: A five-passenger, four-door truck, the Terradyne  
is built for working. The pickup bed stretches 1 1/2 feet; there's 
also a built-in 5,000-watt generator. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEL CVC: While Opel, GM's European arm, doesn't sell cars in  
North America, GM will show off its concept vehicle here. The small 
van includes a glass roof with a storage box for gloves and skis. 
</P>
<P>
	CHEVROLET SSR: The hot-rod truck, the SSR's convertible hardtop  
folds down between the passenger compartment and the pickup bed. 
</P>
<P>
	CHEVROLET TRAVERSE: Chevy calls this SUV the ``family car'' for  
the next generation. Comes with a built-in personal computer with 
Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	PONTIAC PIRANHA: The Piranha is a four-seat coupe that doubles  
as a small cargo hauler -- three of its seats can be folded down. 
The roof has a fabric panel that opens up. 
</P>
<P>
	CADILLAC 2000 CONCEPT: GM designers bill this as Cadillac's  
top-of-the-line sedan for the next century. Night vision, 
fingerprint-based security system standard. 

</P>
<P>
	Source: General Motors Corp.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
