<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell broadly in early trading  
Monday after last week's sell-off on Wall Street. The dollar fell 
against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 189.58 points,  
or 1.09 percent, to 17,411.99 in the first hour of trading. On 
Friday, the index shed 178.69 points, or 1.00 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 105.38 yen, down 0.40 yen from late Friday in  
Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 105.42 yen, also on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, share prices moved lower as sentiment was dampened by  
a sharp fall on Wall Street Friday after Federal Reserve Chairman 
Alan Greenspan expressed concern about U.S. stock prices. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average lost 266.90 points,  
or 2.6 percent, to close at 10,019.71. At one point, the Dow 
slipped below 10,000 points. The average also recorded its worst 
weekly point drop in history, plummeting 630.05 points, or 5.9 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders in Tokyo said there was broad selling across the  
banking, brokerage, retail and high-technology sectors in early 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wall Street is expected to fall further for technical reasons,  
so it is difficult to go bargain hunting now,'' said Sachio 
Ishikawa, general manager of the stock division at Chuo Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan's comments late Thursday suggesting that the stock  
market's great rally might abruptly end, were taken by many to mean 
the Fed would likely raise interest rates at its next Federal Open 
Market Operations meeting on Nov. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock price index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 35.96 points, or 2.44 percent, to 1,474.30. 
The TOPIX fell 26.48 points, or 1.72 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, traders said the dollar was under selling  
pressure amid nervousness over U.S. asset markets. 
</P>
<P>
	That pressure came after inflation fears resulting from the  
announcement Friday that U.S. wholesale prices rose 1.1 percent in 
September, far above the market estimate of 0.5 percent, spurred 
sales of the U.S. currency in New York by fueling further 
speculation that the Fed will raise lending rates next month. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was trading at 115.21 yen, up from  
114.96 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond  
stood at 1.8150 percent, unchanged from Friday's close. Its price 
remained at 99.01 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
