<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tonya Harding Arrives for Pro Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) -- Tonya Harding thrust her hand above her  
head Sunday to give a barometer of her jitters on the eve of her 
professional figure skating debut. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight months after announcing her comeback plans, Harding's  
first competition since the 1994 Lillehammer Olympics has her 
feeling like the new kid at practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very nervous. It's the first time stepping out in front of  
everybody, and I'm just like, `Oh gosh!''' Harding said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 28-year-old Harding will compete against four other women in  
the Pro Skating Championships at the Huntington Civic Arena. The 
technical program will be Monday night and the artistic program 
Tuesday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	The only American woman to land a triple axel in competition,  
she plans to skate with more maturity and less athleticism than 
five years ago. She still plans three triple jumps, but of an 
easier variety. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm more of a well-developed skater, more well-rounded,'' she  
said. ``I've worked at being able to connect my moves more 
gracefully.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Implicated in the 1994 attack on rival skater Nancy Kerrigan,  
Harding is banned for life from competing in an amateur event. But 
the U.S. Figure Skating Association has no jurisdiction over pro 
events. 
</P>
<P>
	After a 20-hour day and two connecting flights, Harding arrived  
at her hotel after midnight Saturday in this Ohio River city of 
60,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Across town from where her debut will take place, Harding held a  
half-hour session amid several male skaters at a smaller rink used 
for youth hockey and skating lessons. 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing a white leotard, she found it difficult adjusting to  
East Coast time and to the arena's cold conditions, often skating 
over to talk with her godmother, Linda Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	Harding fell twice during warmup jumps on the bumpy ice. A  
run-through of her two-minute technical program went smoother. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was real stiff when I first got out there,'' she said,  
reaching for a cup of hot chocolate. ``When I warmed up, I felt 
better. Now all of a sudden I'm cold. I can't wait to go back and 
take a nap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The show has drawn worldwide media interest yet has failed to  
sell out the 5,780-seat Huntington Civic Arena. Temperatures that 
reached 80 degrees outside Sunday hardly conjured up thoughts of 
figure skating. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's football season. The baseball playoffs are going on. It's  
too early for skating,'' said Harding's adviser, Michael Rosenberg. 
``What we've got is 25 million watching on television or reading 
about it. It's not the live crowd. In this case, it's the rest of 
the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The show will be broadcast on ESPN on Oct. 25, Nov. 1 and Nov.  
8. 
</P>
<P>
	Other women entered in the competition include Surya Bonaly,  
Elizabeth Manley, Tonia Kwiatkowski and Rory Burghart, the latter a 
replacement for Pasha Grischuk, who was injured in practice last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	It also will feature competition for men, dance and pairs.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
