<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AL Playoffs Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Fenway Park can be a tough and very loud place for  
visiting teams. And the chants they hear can be rather creative. 
</P>
<P>
	When Cleveland's Manny Ramirez struggled in the AL division  
series, Red Sox fans launched a chorus of ``Manny's Hitless, 
Manny's Hitless.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, after the Yankees' Roger Clemens was knocked out in  
the third inning of his fizzled pitching duel with Pedro Martinez, 
some fans sang, ``Where is Roger?'' Others answered, ``In the 
shower.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And when New York shortstop Derek Jeter came to bat in the first  
inning of Sunday night's Game 4 of the AL championship series, a 
chant rolled through the right-field seats, ``Nomar's Better. 
Nomar's Better,'' a reference to Boston shortstop Nomar 
Garciaparra. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Sox manager Jimy Williams, after three years in Boston,  
thinks he knows why the chants are so original. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got all these colleges in this town. They've got all  
these educated people out there,'' he said. ``That doesn't surprise 
me. All these Harvard grads in town.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Williams was third-base coach for the Braves, the Atlanta  
fans' main demonstration was the ``tomahawk chop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It was intimidating,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Toronto fans were far less expressive when Williams managed  
there from 1986-89. 
</P>
<P>
	``Toronto?'' he asked. The crowds were so quiet, ``You used to  
be able to talk to the first-base coach.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BON VOYAGE:* Yankees manager Joe Torre thinks Game 5 starter  
Orlando Hernandez can handle whatever verbal abuse Fenway fans hurl 
his way. 
</P>
<P>
	When Hernandez arrived in the United States from Cuba, his mode  
of transportation reportedly was something far less luxurious than 
a cruise ship. But it may not have been as rickety as believed. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's to scare him after leaving Cuba and having, you know,  
we really don't know what size boat he came over on,'' Torre said. 
``But whatever it was, it's still the fact that he had to slide out 
of the country and hide somewhere and then be found and all this 
kind of stuff. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the way we got to the ballpark, I know that.''  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CURSE THE CURSE:* Carlton Fisk didn't wait until he threw out  
the first ball Sunday to fire a high, hard one. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Red Sox catcher treated the ``Curse of the Bambino''  
like the pitch from Cincinnati's Pat Darcy he hit for the 
game-winning homer in Game 6 of the 1975 World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston last won the World Series in 1918 and, after the  
following season, traded the Bambino, Babe Ruth, to the Yankees. 
Thus, the ``Curse of the Bambino.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's such a crock,'' Fisk said, ``it's unbelievable.''  
</P>
<P>
	If it's true that Ruth has nothing to do with Boston's  
misfortunes, the Red Sox should win Game 5 Monday night. The 
Bambino's daughter, Julia Ruth Stevens, is scheduled to throw out 
the first pitch. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HAPPY TO BE HERE:* Kent Mercker found a quick way to go from  
fourth place to first -- get traded. That's what happened when St. 
Louis dealt Monday night's probable starter to Boston on Aug. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was one of the best days of my life,'' Mercker, who  
pitched in the playoffs with Atlanta, said at a pregame news 
conference. ``The thought of me having a chance to do that again 
and pitching in games like that and talking on the podium like 
this, it's great.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SIGN OF THE TIMES:*Seeing Clemens get rocked for six runs  
Saturday wasn't enough for Red Sox fans. Some of them still haven't 
forgiven him for leaving as a free agent after the 1996 season. 
</P>
<P>
	So they took their feelings out on a large canvas sign -- about 8  
feet high by 10 feet wide -- near Boston's clubhouse after the game. 
The sign commemorates Clemens' two 20-strikeout games with the Red 
Sox in 1986 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Some fans tugged at it and left the bottom of it in tatters. But  
they couldn't pull it off the brick wall. Soon, four police 
officers came to stand guard by it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still here holding down the fort,'' one said several  
minutes later. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SINGING AND SLINGING:*Bret wasn't the first Saberhagen to hear  
the cheers of the Red Sox crowd. His wife, Lynn, a professional 
singer, received a standing ovation when she performed the National 
Anthem. 
</P>
<P>
	Bret started Game 4 by retiring the Yankees without a run in the  
top of the first. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
