<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991017.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 18:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NiSource Raises Columbia Energy Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HERNDON, Va. (AP) -- NiSource Inc. has upped its offer for  
Columbia Energy Group by 9 percent, or $6 a share, to try to 
persuade Columbia to drop its vigorous, months-long efforts to fend 
off the bid. 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource, facing a deadline today to announce the results of a  
$68 a share offer initially made in June, said Sunday it would pay 
$74 a share for the Virginia company. The increase would boost the 
value of the deal to $6.1 billion from $5.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The sweetened bid offers shareholders a 22 percent premium over  
Columbia's Friday's closing price of $60.50 on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's offer is the right price for the right company at the  
right time,'' said Gary L. Neale, NiSource's chairman, president 
and chief executive officer. ``The $74 cash per share we are 
offering is well above the value that Columbia, on its own, in any 
reasonable time frame, could provide its shareholders and allows 
Columbia shareholders to receive their share of the value created 
by the combination of the two companies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The offer expires at midnight Nov. 12.  
</P>
<P>
	In an overture to Columbia's management, Neale said Columbia  
Energy Chairman Oliver G. Richard III would become vice chairman of 
the combined company, and that he and four other members of 
Columbia's board would be invited to join an expanded NiSource 
board. 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource, based in Merrillville, Ind., said its bid has received  
``substantial'' support from Columbia shareholders, with 44.4 
million shares, or nearly 54 percent, agreeing to the offer, as of 
midnight Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement Sunday, Columbia Energy said its board would  
review the higher offer but urged shareholders not to act before 
the board had made a recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	Maria Hibbs, a spokeswoman for NiSource, said size and geography  
are becoming increasingly critical to succeeding in the changing 
energy industry. She said NiSource and Columbia Energy would make a 
good fit in a natural gas distribution corridor stretching from the 
Chicago market to New England. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Columbia launched a final appeal to shareholders to  
reject the previous NiSource bid. The Herndon-based company also 
paid for ads in Indiana newspapers claiming that the buyout would 
harm consumers there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shouldn't NiSource be spending its time and money trying to  
reduce harmful smokestack emissions and protecting the welfare of 
its customers and communities in Indiana?'' said one ad, which 
accused NiSource of having a ``disturbing environmental record.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource is the parent company of Northern Indiana Public  
Service Co. and Bay State Gas Co. in Massachusetts. It would become 
one of the nation's biggest natural gas companies if the takeover 
succeeds. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy is involved in natural gas exploration,  
production, transmission, storage and distribution as well as 
propane sales and electric power generation, sales and trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Columbia Energy attempted to buy Pittsburgh-based  
Consolidated Natural Gas. But CNG rejected the offer and chose to 
proceed with a previously planned merger with Richmond, Va.-based 
Dominion Resources Inc. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
