<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 22:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farms Turn Fair-Like for Customers / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GASPORT, N.Y. (AP) -- Unmistakable signs of the fall harvest in  
New York: The rumble of tractors through sweet-smelling apple 
orchards. Piles of pumpkins at roadside stands. The steel-drum 
sound of a Calypso band and the smell of popcorn wafting above the 
heads of children waiting for pony rides. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the annual marriage of farm meets fair as growers with  
loads of produce to sell reach out to the buying public. 
</P>
<P>
	With many supermarket chains giving their produce sections a  
homegrown farmers' market feel, it's no easy task persuading busy 
shoppers to make an extra detour to the country. 
</P>
<P>
	But with foreign competition driving wholesale prices down, many  
farmers can't afford or aren't willing to lose their 
direct-to-consumer business. So they pull out all the stops to keep 
families coming to them, carving out cornfield mazes, hiring 
magicians, setting up petting zoos and opening restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's become a case of the tail wags the dog,'' said Bob Brown,  
owner of Brown's Berry Patch in Waterport. His farm's gift shop, 
deli, ice cream counters, storybook-themed play areas and live 
animal displays draw more customers than the pick-your-own produce 
business they were set up to boost. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's become more and more entertainment and less and less  
produce,'' Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's demanding, yes, handling extra staff, advertising and  
licensing on top of the perpetual weather and crop price worries. 
But with childhood memories of his father picketing an apple packer 
for an extra penny a pound, Brown is determined not to become 
dependent on the processing industry for his livelihood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, we sell Pepsi,'' he said. ``I never wanted to sell Pepsi,  
but if that's what the public wants, you're a fool not to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state's Guide to Farm-Fresh Foods lists more than 1,000  
farms that sell at least some of their harvest directly to the 
public, but there has been no survey to determine how many farms 
have gone beyond the traditional roadside stand. 
</P>
<P>
	The number is growing, said Pete Gregg, spokesman for the New  
York Department of Agriculture and Markets. 
</P>
<P>
	As a farmer, ``you have more control over your prices, you have  
more control over your operation and you have more control over 
your destiny when you're directly marketing your product to the 
consumer,'' Gregg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers who may get $7 per bushel of apples from a packing house  
can charge twice that at their own shops and still be well below 
supermarket prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a win-win situation because the consumer also gets to  
pick the produce that appeals to them,'' Gregg said. ``They're 
getting fresh local produce, which is always going to taste the 
best, plus it's a great family thing to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trend goes beyond produce. Maple syrup producers offer  
pancake breakfasts, wineries have added cafes, Christmas tree 
growers provide cross-country ski trails and cut-your-own 
operations and herb farms host culinary seminars. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an exciting thing that's happening in agriculture right  
now,'' Gregg said. ``There's a large amount of consumers and a 
large amount of farms, and marrying the two is really a key to the 
future of agriculture here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991017.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 20:55:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Missed Chances Doom Braves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For the Atlanta Braves, Sunday's Game 5 of the  
National League Championship Series was a frustrating string of 
missed opportunities, 15 innings of aggravation. 
</P>
<P>
	They loaded the bases in consecutive innings, both times without  
benefit of a base hit, and failed to score each time in a game they 
lost 4-3 to the New York Mets after taking the lead in the top half 
of the 15th and needing just three outs to reach the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	This was a game the Braves should have won earlier and thought  
they had finally won despite having a runner thrown out at the 
plate and leaving a record 19 runners on base. 
</P>
<P>
	Even in the inning they scored their first two runs, they came  
away with less than they might have. 
</P>
<P>
	The bases-loaded situations might have been turning points if  
Atlanta had not wasted so many other chances. Perhaps the most 
painful came in the 13th inning when Keith Lockhart singled with 
two out and tried to score from first on Chipper Jones' two-out 
double. He was thrown out by at least 10 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Batting just .198 in the first four games of the series, the  
Braves had one brief breakthrough, stringing consecutive doubles by 
Bret Boone and Jones and a single by Brian Jordan to tie the score 
2-2 in the fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	When Ryan Klesko walked, there were two on and no outs. But Orel  
Hershiser came out of the Mets bullpen to strike out Andruw Jones 
and Eddie Perez and get Walt Weiss on a roller to first base. 
</P>
<P>
	For the next 10 innings, the Braves had plenty of chances but  
couldn't score. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta left two runners on base in the fifth, wasting Gerald  
Williams' double. But the Braves' best chances came in the sixth 
and seventh, even though they never got a hit in either inning. 
</P>
<P>
	After Klesko, leading off, reached on an error by John Olerud,  
he was bunted to second. After walking Perez intentionally, 
Hershiser then walked Weiss unintentionally to load the bases. With 
pitcher Greg Maddux at bat, manager Bobby Cox put on the squeeze, 
despite a two-strike count. Maddux missed the bunt for strike three 
and Klesko had no chance coming down the line and was tagged out to 
end the inning. 
</P>
<P>
	An inning later, the Braves were back, knocking on the door  
again. 
</P>
<P>
	Boone was hit by a pitch with one out and Turk Wendell came on  
to strike out Chipper Jones. Boone stole second on the third strike 
and Jordan was walked intentionally, the first two balls thrown by 
Wendell, the last two by Dennis Cook, brought in to force Cox to 
pinch hit for Klesko. 
</P>
<P>
	When righty swinging Brian Hunter came to bat, Pat Mahones  
relieved for New York but walked the pinch hitter, loading the 
bases again. Then he got Andruw Jones on a fly ball, ending the 
threat. 
</P>
<P>
	It was like that all night for Atlanta. The Braves wasted a  
leadoff double by Perez in the third inning and one-out doubles by 
Williams in the fifth and Weiss in the eighth. In the 10th, Perez 
opened with a single and pinch-runner Howard Battle stole second, 
but Atlanta couldn't get the run home. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, in the 15th, a triple by Lockhart drove in the go-ahead  
run. But the Mets weren't done. 
</P>
<P>
	When Robin Ventura delivered the winning hit, the Braves ran out  
of chances and now they won't get anymore until Tuesday when the 
series returns to Atlanta for Game 6. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
