<HEADLINE> N.Y. Leader To Back John McCain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a blow to George W. Bush, one of his most  
influential New York backers is switching allegiances to back 
presidential rival John McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Rep. Guy Molinari, a powerful Republican who had urged  
the Texas governor to seek the presidency, said he had decided to 
``place principle above politics'' and become McCain's New York 
chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement prepared for his announcement today, Molinari did  
not criticize Bush but offered a cryptic explanation for his change 
of heart. ``Candidates -- both Democratic and Republican alike -- 
define their beliefs and shape their convictions by taking polls. 
John McCain is a notable exception.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The statement was provided by the McCain campaign.  
</P>
<P>
	Molinari, who served in the House from 1981 to 1989, is in his  
fourth term as Staten Island borough president. He was a key New 
York supporter of former President George Bush, the Texas 
governor's father. 
</P>
<P>
	Molinari has been feuding with New York Gov. George Pataki,  
Bush's top supporter in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Welcoming the change of heart, McCain said, ``I'm humbled to  
accept the support of Guy Molinari.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Arizona senator and former Vietnam prisoner of war has  
narrowed the gap in polls against Bush in New Hampshire, the 
first-in-the-nation primary state. Though still far behind Bush in 
money-raising and the polls, McCain hopes to stagger the 
front-runner in New Hampshire and the follow-up primary in South 
Carolina, a state with many military veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Bush's strengths is a long list of endorsements from  
party leaders such as Molinari. 
</P>
<P>
	Molinari said he respects Bush, and noted that it would make  
sense to continue backing the GOP front-runner. ``But my respect 
for John McCain and the values he represents compel me to place 
principle above politics,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement did not explain why he backed Bush initially,  
knowing McCain was a rival. 
</P>
<P>
	He said McCain ``is best able to continue the legacy of  
leadership of George Bush and Ronald Reagan.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
