<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Quake Victims To Get Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey's leaders promised Sunday that  
the hundreds of thousands of victims of August's devastating 
earthquake would be out of cold tents and in homes by the end of 
November. 
</P>
<P>
	President Suleyman Demirel and Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit  
toured the hard-hit cities of Yalova, Izmit and Adapazari to mark 
the construction of 6,400 prefabricated houses. 
</P>
<P>
	They are the first of 32,000 temporary houses the government  
promised would be ready by Nov. 30, the Anatolia news agency 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The cold, wet weather has added to the misery of the quake  
survivors, many of whom have been living in leaky tents. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the strength of our state and people and the help of  
friendly nations, we will heal this wound,'' Demirel said in 
Yalova, a seaside resort 25 miles south of Istanbul. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, the government announced state aid of up to $12,700  
for those whose homes were ruined in the quake and who want to buy 
or build a new home. 
</P>
<P>
	Demirel said the government would build 60,000 permanent homes  
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said it also would help families rent homes, as  
well as compensate for the family members' deaths and for 
disabilities that resulted from the quake. 
</P>
<P>
	The 7.4-magnitude tremor on Aug. 17 killed more than 17,000  
people in Turkey's industrial heartland. 
</P>
<P>
	The state was criticized for failing in the first days after the  
disaster to organize rescue operations and distribute aid. Public 
anger, still running high, grew when authorities began distributing 
poor-quality tents, some of which weren't waterproof. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the earth has continued to tremble in Turkey, where a  
3.8-magnitude quake shook the Aegean port city of Izmir early 
Sunday, Istanbul's Kandilli Observatory said. It was not seen as an 
aftershock to the Aug. 17 temblor. No damages or injuries were 
reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
