<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Web Sites Offering Luxury Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shoppers are buying lots of books, videos and  
toys on the Internet these days, but are they ready to purchase 
diamond necklaces or designer suits online? 
</P>
<P>
	The test may come this holiday season. Dozens of Web sites --  
from traditional retailers to startups -- are flooding the 
marketplace with all sorts of luxury goods, including Prada 
pocketbooks and Rolex watches. 
</P>
<P>
	But getting people to actually click on the ``buy'' button --  
especially from e-tailers they've never heard of -- may be tough. 
</P>
<P>
	``Selling luxury goods online is nothing like selling most other  
things on the Web,'' said Michael May, an analyst at the Internet 
research firm Jupiter Communications. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got the issue of what is real and what is a knockoff  
... the issue of price, with some sites discounting and others that 
don't,'' he said. ``But that doesn't mean shoppers won't buy 
expensive stuff online. They just may proceed with caution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The luxury goods market is already big business in the  
traditional retailing world. Sales last year totaled $133 billion 
as the robust economy and surging stock market helped encourage 
shoppers to buy expensive clothing and accessories. 
</P>
<P>
	Many expect luxury sales to eventually flourish on the Internet,  
given the potential for a vastly increased selection and the high 
incomes of those who buy online. About a quarter of the 38 million 
U.S. households that were online last year made more than $75,000 a 
year. That's about a third more than the average American 
household, according to Jupiter Communications. 
</P>
<P>
	But demand for upscale products online so far has been fairly  
small. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Internet is still new. When someone is first going online,  
they won't buy a diamond ring, but I think that as shoppers become 
more comfortable with the Web, they will be more willing to go for 
the higher-priced stuff,'' said Seema Williams, an analyst at 
Forrester Research, an Internet research firm in Cambridge, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Believing that the online luxury market will soon take off, many  
merchants have opened stores selling just high-end goods on the Web 
in the last year. This month alone, more than a dozen companies are 
launching new or redesigned Web sites, just in time for the start 
of the holiday shopping season. 
</P>
<P>
	Many see big profits since the markup on luxury goods is  
significant, which means they can make more on each item sold than 
those merchants selling smaller ticket items such as books or toys. 
</P>
<P>
	As the category expands, however, there is increasing concern  
about how the Internet will change the luxury business. Since 
shoppers can scour the Web for the best deals, many merchants and 
manufacturers worry how that will affect pricing. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, there is virtually no way to control counterfeit  
goods and it is sometimes hard to differentiate Web sites selling 
fakes from those offering legitimate products. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough. You don't want someone selling a Prada pocketbook  
for next to nothing or selling a fake Prada,'' said May, the 
Jupiter analyst. ``When that happens, the notion of luxury becomes 
a commodity and the business model crumbles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nancy Epstein, of Laguna Beach, Calif., says she buys expensive  
things online only at Web sites with reputable names. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be terrible if I spent lots of money on something  
like a Louis Vuitton purse, and it ended up not being real,'' she 
said. ``That makes me think twice before buying online.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the luxury space getting more crowded, analysts point to a  
few sites that will give shoppers fair pricing and quality 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	One is neimanmarcus.com, which is expected to be launched by the  
venerable retailer Neiman Marcus on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoppers will find more than 500 items on neimanmarcus.com --  
from many top-of-the-line designers, including Gucci and Donna 
Karan -- and the inventory is expected to grow in the coming months. 
Live customer service is available on the site as is a unique 
merchandising service that helps shoppers match clothes and 
accessories. 
</P>
<P>
	What makes neimanmarcus.com stand out is its link to its already  
reputable stores and catalog. Every item is guaranteed and 
returnable. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts also laud Internet startup Ashford.com, which currently  
sells 10,000 different styles of watches, fragrances, leather 
accessories, sunglasses and writing instruments, including goods 
from Rolex, TAG Heuer and Cartier. On Monday, it is expected to 
announce it will begin selling designer jewelry and diamonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Some merchandise is discounted. Every item it sells is  
guaranteed to be authentic and there is a 30-day money back 
guarantee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was pleasantly surprised at the experience I had at  
Ashford.com,'' said Dan George, of Carlsbad, Calif., who bought a 
Breitling watch on the site for nearly $1,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't sure what to expect. But they had more watches than  
any of the local jewelry stores, and everything, down to the box 
that the watch came in, was done absolutely right.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
