<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dolphins 31, Patriots 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Damon Huard, filling in after Dan Marino  
left early with a sore shoulder, threw a 5-yard touchdown pass to 
Stanley Pritchett with 23 seconds left Sunday to give the Miami 
Dolphins a 31-30 win over the New England Patriots. 
</P>
<P>
	Huard, who had thrown just nine passes in his first two seasons,  
replaced Marino following the Dolphins' second series. He threw an 
interception that Ty Law brought back 24 yards for a score, but 
also threw a 69-yard TD pass to Tony Martin and the 5-yard score to 
Pritchett on a 59-yard drive on which he converted three third 
downs -- a third-and-10, a third-and-9 and a third-and-5. 
</P>
<P>
	After falling behind 14-0, Olindo Mare kept Miami (4-1) in the  
game with six field goals -- breaking an NFL record by kicking four 
or more for the fourth straight game. His 53-yarder with just over 
five minutes left set the stage for Miami's final drive. 
</P>
<P>
	Huard was sacked nine times by the Patriots -- a record for the  
most allowed by the Dolphins. But he also completed 24 of 40 passes 
for 240 yards and scrambled six times for 54 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second straight last-minute victory for Miami, which  
came from behind last week in Indianapolis to win 34-31. That 
victory was engineered by Marino, the week after he was criticized 
by coach Jimmy Johnson following a 23-18 home loss to Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	For New England (4-2), it was the second straight last-minute  
loss. The Patriots dropped a 16-14 decision in Kansas City last 
week when Adam Vinatieri missed a 32-yard field goal in the final 
seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Marino started Sunday but clearly was under par. He surpassed  
60,000 career yards on his only completion, an 8-yarder, but his 
second pass was intercepted by Andy Katzenmoyer and returned 57 
yards for a touchdown. The interception was forced by Lawyer 
Milloy's safety blitz. 
</P>
<P>
	Marino, who clearly couldn't throw well, was lifted after a  
short pass for Pritchett fell well short of the target. 
</P>
<P>
	Vinatieri was three-for-three Sunday, hitting from 41, 39 and 34  
yards, but he was most of the New England offense. 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots' only offensive touchdown came on a 29-yard pass  
from Drew Bledsoe to Tony Simmons with 1:03 left in the first half. 
It was countered by Mare's 45-yarder that made it 24-19 at 
intermission. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
