<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jaguars 24, Browns 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Mark Brunell got hurt. The  
Jacksonville Jaguars stumbled, bumbled and embarrassed themselves. 
Finally, it was Jay Fiedler who smoothed things over. 
</P>
<P>
	Entering in the third quarter for a banged-up Brunell, the  
fourth-year veteran from Dartmouth directed two touchdown drives 
and another for a field goal Sunday to help the Jaguars defeat the 
Cleveland Browns 24-7. 
</P>
<P>
	Before he left with bruised ribs, Brunell continued to struggle,  
throwing for 109 yards and leading Jacksonville (5-1) to just a 
pair of field goals. 
</P>
<P>
	Until Fiedler entered, it seemed almost any other team but the  
expansion Browns might have beaten the Jaguars, who continued to 
struggle on offense in the absence of former offensive coordinator 
Chris Palmer, who left to coach the Browns (0-6). 
</P>
<P>
	Jacksonville trailed 7-6 late in the third quarter when  
linebacker Bryan Schwartz forced a fumble that was recovered by 
Kevin Hardy at the Cleveland 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Three plays later, Fiedler lobbed a pass to the corner of the  
end zone to Kyle Brady, who extended for a nice catch in double 
coverage and a 7-yard touchdown. A 2-point conversion made it 14-7. 
</P>
<P>
	After Jacksonville forced a punt, Fiedler directed the best  
drive of the day, a 70-yard march that included completions to 
three different receivers and ended with a 2-yard touchdown run by 
James Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	Playing for the injured Fred Taylor, Stewart finished with 58  
yards on 23 carries. Fiedler went 12-for-14 for 113 yards and also 
scrambled three times for 27 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	When Fiedler entered, the Jaguars defense perked up, as well,  
coming up with four sacks and shutting down a Cleveland offense 
that effectively ate up small chunks of yardage through the first 
half. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Couch completed his first 12 passes and finished 18-for-23  
for 161 yards, running through his progressions with confidence and 
staying poised in the pocket when the Jacksonville pass rush 
developed. 
</P>
<P>
	He flipped a short screen to Terry Kirby for a 9-yard touchdown  
late in the second quarter that gave the Browns a 7-3 lead and 
brought boos from a crowd that expected more from the AFC Central 
champions. 
</P>
<P>
	The embarrassment extended beyond just football.  
</P>
<P>
	Late in the first half, Jaguars offensive line coach Mike Maser  
ran well onto the field to protest a hit on Brunell, who was 
lightly shoved to the ground by Browns linebacker Jamir Miller. 
Maser was hit for an unsportsmanlike conduct penalty, pulling the 
Jaguars out of scoring range. 
</P>
<P>
	In the fourth quarter, Jaguars linebacker Brant Boyer got  
involved in a shoving match with teammate Gary Walker as the 
defense was coming off the field. The jawing -- and shoving -- 
continued on the sideline until Brunell, out of the game but still 
on the sideline at that point, stepped in to calm things down. 
</P>
<P>
	Brunell completed 12 of 18 passes and once again had trouble  
leading the Jaguars to touchdowns. Twice in the first half, he 
moved Jacksonville inside the 20-yard line, but both times, the 
Jaguars settled for field goals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
