<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes, Dole Target GOP Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Steve Forbes and Elizabeth Dole, trying to make  
headway against the juggernaut of Republican front-runner George W. 
Bush, on Sunday urged GOP women activists to give a second look at 
their bids for the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, a conservative publisher able to tap his personal wealth  
to challenge Bush, presented himself as a reform-minded 
``independent outsider'' who offers more substance and specific 
positions than Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	He drew repeated ovations from the 2,000 delegates at the  
National Federation of Republican Women's last convention before 
the 2000 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole got a heroine's welcome at the convention a few hours  
later. She was introduced as a lifelong trailblazer and the first 
woman with a credible shot at a major party presidential 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Federation President Mary Jo Arndt of Illinois urged delegates  
to write out a generous check to Mrs. Dole, even if they support 
Bush or someone else, as a tribute to her courage. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither candidate, however, got the star treatment given Friday  
night to Bush, the governor of Texas, who has a commanding lead in 
the polls and has broken all fund-raising records. The audience for 
Bush's speech was considerably larger than those who stuck around 
for Forbes and Mrs. Dole on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	But the two candidates showed no sign of preparing to quit the  
race. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes was the more aggressive in taking on Bush and a  
Democratic candidate, Vice President Al Gore. He appeared to lump 
the two together at one point, complaining about the ``gap, the 
disconnect, between the political culture'' and ordinary citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole was the sentimental favorite of the convention,  
though. She was surrounded by autograph-seekers and well-wishers as 
she sat at the block-long head table. 
</P>
<P>
	She was repeatedly interrupted with applause as she gave her  
standard campaign speech, complete with stories from the campaign 
trail and numerous references to ``my husband, Bob,'' the 1996 GOP 
nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	She said more than half her contributors are women -- an aide  
called her ``the only candidate with no gender gap'' -- and that her 
campaign has attracted young people and others who rarely get 
involved in politics. She was introduced as ``one of America's most 
powerful and admired women, always ahead of her time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like Forbes, she called for tax cuts and parental choice in  
education. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
