<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox One Loss From Elimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The last time the Boston Red Sox went to the World  
Series, they made it by rallying from a 3-1 deficit in the 1986 AL 
Championship Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen frustrating years later, that's the only way they can  
get back. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday night's 9-2 loss to the New York Yankees in Game 4 of the  
ALCS left the Red Sox with just one option: win Monday night or 
extend their championship drought to 81 years. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Red Sox haven't given up.  
</P>
<P>
	A note on their clubhouse bulletin board after Sunday's loss  
read: ``Pack for travel after Monday night's game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To make that trip back to New York for a Game 6 on Wednesday  
night, the Red Sox hope left-hander Kent Mercker, who has a 6.35 
ERA in 5 2-3 postseason innings this year, can come through. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll start against Orlando Hernandez, the Yankees' hottest  
pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're really not looking at the three games right now,''  
Boston third baseman John Valentin said. ``Now, obviously, you have 
to look at tomorrow. We're facing a tough pitcher and he's had 
success against us in the past and we've got to go get him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Bret Saberhagen pitched better than in his two other  
postseason starts this year -- one earned run and five hits in six 
innings -- but the Red Sox still couldn't beat the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Two questionable calls by umpires didn't help.  
</P>
<P>
	Second-base umpire Tim Tschida admitted he was wrong when he  
ruled Chuck Knoblauch had tagged Jose Offerman on the front end of 
a double play in the eighth with New York ahead 3-2. 
</P>
<P>
	And in the ninth, first-base umpire Dale Scott ruled Nomar  
Garciaparra out at first on a grounder to third baseman Scott 
Brosius. Replays indicated Garciaparra beat the throw. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tough loss,'' Saberhagen said. ``I think the big thing is  
we've got to put this behind us and play baseball like we have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Boston won the World Series was 1918 with Babe  
Ruth pitching the team to victory in Games 1 and 4. That was the 
Red Sox's fifth and most recent title. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the 1920 season, Ruth was traded to the Yankees, who are  
closing in on their 25th World Series crown. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the Red Sox have a Ruth on their side. The Babe's daughter,  
Julia Ruth Stevens, is scheduled to throw out the first pitch 
Monday night. She has been a summer resident of New Hampshire for 
50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Just before she moved there, the Red Sox had a chance to go to  
the World Series, in 1948. Boston and Cleveland tied for the AL 
pennant, but the Indians won a one-game playoff 8-3 at Fenway Park. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Boston catcher Carlton Fisk threw out the first  
pitch. It was Fisk who waved his winning homer fair in Game 6 of 
the 1975 World Series. Once again, a title proved elusive as 
Cincinnati won the championship the next day 4-3. 
</P>
<P>
	Improbable as it is, it's not impossible for the Red Sox to  
climb off the brink of elimination by winning three straight games. 
</P>
<P>
	They did it in the 1986 ALCS by beating the California Angels  
after trailing 5-2 going into the top of the ninth of Game 5. The 
Red Sox scored four runs in the inning and went on to a 7-6 win in 
11 innings. They won the series by winning the next two games 10-4 
and 8-1, with current Yankee Roger Clemens pitching the clincher. 
</P>
<P>
	They also won three straight games to take this year's best-of-5  
division series, beating the Cleveland Indians 9-3, 23-7 and 12-8. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're down three games to one,'' Nomar Garciaparra said. ``Can  
we come back? Sure we can. We did it before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the Yankees are the defending World Series champions and  
have a much better pitching staff than the Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Red Sox have a long history of October anguish that  
continued Sunday with some bad plays by themselves and bad calls by 
umpires. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Dan Duquette was asked his general feeling about  
those calls. 
</P>
<P>
	``My general feeling,'' he said, ``is that we need to win  
tomorrow's game.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
