<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 14 Held Hostage in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Suspected guerrillas posing as  
passengers hijacked a tourist boat off Colombia's Pacific coast, 
abducting 14 men before releasing the vessel, its captain and the 
women and children aboard, the navy reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Four assailants with concealed weapons boarded the boat Saturday  
in Buenaventura, a major western port, then forced it to land at a 
beach where they took away the male passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	``An armed man took the steering wheel, threatened us and made  
us look downward,'' Patricia Sanchez, the wife of one of the men 
still hostage, told Radionet radio. 
</P>
<P>
	After reaching the beach, Sanchez said she grabbed hold of her  
husband's hand and tried to stay with him. But he and his captors 
insisted she remain behind with the other women and children. 
</P>
<P>
	No group has claimed responsibility. But the action appeared to  
be another in a wave of rebel abductions that have increasingly 
exposed ordinary Colombians to the dangers of the country's 35-year 
conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	The expedition was headed for a popular beach when it was forced  
off course, the navy said. After the captors fled with their 
hostages, the captain piloted the ship back to Buenaventura late 
Saturday with the women and children on board. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the navy's report, freed passengers said the  
hostage-takers declared they were punishing the boat's owner for 
refusing to make extortion payments to the country's largest rebel 
band, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC. 
</P>
<P>
	The FARC -- which finances its insurgency through kidnappings,  
extortion and by protecting the drug trade -- is set to begin peace 
talks with the government on Oct. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	A smaller leftist guerrilla group, the National Liberation Army,  
has also kidnapped hundreds of people this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Seeking ransoms and a seat at the peace table, the ELN has  
hijacked a domestic airliner in flight, raided a Catholic Mass and 
intercepted a fishing expedition in the Caribbean. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
