<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton For Campaign Finance Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTICELLO, N.Y. (AP) -- Senate contender Hillary Rodham Clinton  
told about 600 Democrats at a political fund-raiser Sunday that as 
an almost-candidate she has become an even bigger booster of 
campaign finance reform. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that I'm leaning so far in becoming a candidate that if I  
leaned any further I'd fall over, I really support campaign finance 
reform,'' said Mrs. Clinton, whose supporters have vowed to raise 
$25 million for her race. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the weeks and months ahead I'm going to have more to say  
about that because I think it is imperative that we all, as 
citizens of our democracy, stand up for change in the way that we 
finance campaigns,'' the first lady said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, a frequent campaigner who has not formally  
declared her candidacy, offered no details about what she might 
propose. 
</P>
<P>
	She starred at a $55-a-person Sullivan County Democratic  
Committee's fund-raising dinner at a Catskill Mountains landmark, 
Kutsher's Country Club. It was the second such event she has 
headlined in three days and the third in three weeks in her adopted 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	While Mrs. Clinton has regularly sought to help Democratic  
congressional candidates across New York, in recent weeks she has 
begun lending her fame to local party organizations in preparation 
for next year's Senate race. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton camp believes that helping local Democrats,  
particularly outside heavily Democratic New York City, could pay 
dividends for the first lady in a U.S. senate race against the 
probable opponent, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. The 
suburban counties surrounding New York City and the upstate area, 
where Republicans tend to do well, are expected to be key 
battlegrounds in the Senate race. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent days, Mrs. Clinton has stepped up her campaigning,  
drawing distinctions between herself and Giuliani, without 
mentioning the mayor by name. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
