<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thornfield Wins Canadian Intl. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Thornfield, the longest shot in the field and  
owned by Steve Stavro, a part-owner of the Toronto Maple Leafs and 
Toronto Raptors, overtook Courteous in the deep stretch and went on 
to win the $1.56 million Canadian International by a length on 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The British-bred Courteous appeared to have the race well in  
hand, leading by seven lengths a half-mile into the 1 1/2-mile race at 
Woodbine Racetrack. Even turning for home, Courteous seemed in 
control, leading by five lengths. 
</P>
<P>
	But Courteous's blazing pace hurt down the stretch as the  
4-year-old began to wilt, allowing the onrushing Thornfield to make 
up ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Thornfield, a 5-year-old gelding, was timed on a good turf  
course in 2:32 1-5. The victory was worth $936,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Thornfield paid $39.70, $11.80 and $6.60 and became the fifth  
Canadian-bred winner of this event since 1958. Thornfield also 
became the first International winner to be sired by a prior victor 
of this event (Sky Classic in 1991). 
</P>
<P>
	American-bred Fruits of Love, who went off as the 8-5 favorite,  
finished second, paying $4.60 and $3.20. 
</P>
<P>
	Courteous, who was a 15-1 long shot, held on to third and paid  
$7.40. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-horse field was truly an international one, with  
entries from Canada, the United States, England, Chile, Ireland and 
Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian International was the fourth stop on the inaugural  
Emirates World Series racing championship. The nine-race circuit 
began March 28 with the $5 million Dubai World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Each race in the championship carries a purse of at least $1  
million and will be run over either 1 1/4 or 1 1/2 miles. The horse that 
accumulates the most points over the course of the year will earn a 
$1 million bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the circuit's leading horses skipped the International,  
including Irish-bred Daylami, who tops the overall standings with 
26 points. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
