<DOCNO> APW19991017.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 15:40:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Incumbant Winning Catalan Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARCELONA, Spain (AP) -- The nationalist party maintained its  
grip on power in Sunday's regional parliamentary elections in 
prosperous northeastern Catalonia, but its rival Socialists still 
scored major gains, preliminary results indicated. 
</P>
<P>
	Catalan President Jordi Pujol, the 69-year-old leader of the  
Convergence and Union Party who has held office for 19 years, 
claimed victory at a a Barcelona hotel as hundreds of supporters 
cheered wildly, ``President, President!'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have won a sixth time, not the Socialists, so we will  
govern Catalonia,'' Pujol shouted back. 
</P>
<P>
	With 96.7 percent of the vote counted, Pujol's party had won 56  
seats in the 135-seat Parliament, compared with 52 seats for the 
Socialists and 12 for the Popular Party of Spanish Prime Minister 
Jose Maria Aznar. Esquerra Republicana, which advocates Catalan 
independence, won 12 seats, and the Green Party won three. 
</P>
<P>
	The win would mean a sixth consecutive term for Pujol, a  
national power broker. Pujol had faced his toughest challenger in 
years in the leader of the Socialists -- the popular former 
Barcelona Mayor Pascual Maragall. 
</P>
<P>
	The results showed Pujol's party short of a majority 68 seats  
and indicated major gains for the Socialists, who held only 34 
seats in Parliament going into the elections. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think that a new stage is opened in the parliamentary and  
political history of Catalonia'', said Joaquim Nadal, who was 
second in the Socialist's list of candidates for the presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	Police reported scattered incidents of violence overnight.  
Assailants hurled gasoline bombs at automatic cash machines, a 
police van and a political party office in Granollers, Barcelona, 
and Barbera del Valles. Police blamed the attacks on young 
independence advocates. Damage was described as moderate. 
</P>
<P>
	Catalonia, with its capital in Barcelona, is Spain's most  
prosperous region with 6.1 million people and a thriving economy. 
</P>
<P>
	For many Spaniards, Pujol, 69, personifies Catalan nationalism.  
He promotes himself as the guardian of the Catalan language and 
culture and during his 19 years in office has gained greater 
administrative powers for the region. 
</P>
<P>
	He earned a reputation for defending Catalonia during Gen.  
Francisco Franco's four-decade dictatorship. 
</P>
<P>
	Regardless of the election's outcome, Maragall, is the first  
candidate to come within striking distance of Pujol. Maragall was 
highly praised for attracting the Summer Olympics to the city in 
1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Turnout was 46.36 percent among the region's 5.3 million voters  
two hours before the polling booth closed, the lowest of the 
region's sixth election since democracy was restored in 1978. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
