<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 18:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> What's Next for Wall Street? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks swooned last week under an unusual  
barrage of bad news. Market watchers are divided on whether stocks 
can rebound in the week to come, as expectations of good news about 
corporate profits and potentially bad news about inflation battle 
for investors' attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, bad news won out, driving the Dow Jones industrial  
average down 630.05 points, or 5.9 percent, to close at 10,019.71. 
It was the Dow's worst week ever in terms of points lost, and the 
worst of the decade in terms of percentages. 
</P>
<P>
	Market analysts aren't sure whether the decline has laid ground  
for a further selloff, or opened the door to bargain-hunting 
investors who could once again propel stocks higher. 
</P>
<P>
	``We may have reached an oversold condition that will bring  
buyers back in,'' said Eugene E. Peroni, director of equity 
research at John Nuveen &AMP; Co. ``And that could set the stage for a 
better and more sustainable move later on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other analysts say stocks could be in for another rough week as  
last week's main menace -- the fear that signs of inflation will 
prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates for the third 
time this year -- remains unresolved. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed left rates unchanged at its last meeting, but hinted  
that it would boost rates if inflation appears to be escalating. 
That set a stage for fitful trading as investors watch carefully 
for any nascent signs of price pressures, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	That proved true on Friday, when a sharper-than-expected  
increase in the Producer Price Index sparked selling on Wall 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market can handle higher rates, but it cannot handle  
uncertainty,'' said Peter Canelo, U.S. investment strategist at 
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``By failing to raise rates, the Fed 
opted to extend this torture for another month,'' until its 
policy-making group holds its next meeting Nov. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	The next major barometer of inflation will be the Consumer Price  
Index, due out from the Labor Department on Tuesday. If it shows 
that prices are on the rise, stocks could be in for another fall, 
analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, most market watchers continue to hope buyers will step  
back in if the next round of corporate profit reports is as strong 
as expected. Companies are expected to benefit from robust economic 
growth. Earnings should look especially good in comparison to the 
third quarter of 1998, when most businesses struggled with the 
fallout from Asia's financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, strong reports from companies like Apple and Boeing  
were outweighed by disappointments from Intel and Raytheon. In the 
coming week, industry leaders like Citigroup, Ford, Microsoft and 
IBM will compete for investors' attention as they divulge their 
earnings results. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, strong earnings may not be enough to lift investors'  
spirits if the market's decline has eroded the optimism that has 
characterized the stock market for nearly 10 years, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Throughout this bull market, people have proven willing to buy  
on the market's dips,'' said Michael Metz, portfolio manager at 
CIBC Oppenheimer. ``If people become less willing to do that, it 
would be troubling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Noting that some of the market's worst performances in history  
have come on the Monday following a Friday selloff, some analysts 
suggested that investors may have used the weekend to solidify 
their plans to get out of the market. 
</P>
<P>
	``While stocks may experience a short-lived bounce to start on  
Monday, investors will likely be overtaken by fears that compounded 
over the weekend,'' said Brian G. Belski, chief investment 
strategist at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City, Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	But by the same token, stocks may also benefit if investors  
return from the weekend with a sense of calm about the market's 
fundamental strength, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's some cynicism and skittishness out there, but we have  
not sensed panic in the streets,'' said Jim Weiss, deputy chief 
investment officer for equities at State Street Research and 
Management Co. in Boston. ``I expect to see some buying on a 
selective basis.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
