<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 47 Injured on Hong Kong-Bound Jet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- A China Southern Airlines jet ran into strong  
turbulence and plunged 2,000 feet shortly before it landed in Hong 
Kong on Sunday, injuring 47 passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the injured were hospitalized in serious condition,  
including one American and one Japanese, said Dr. N. K. Leung, 
chief executive of the government-run Princess Margaret Hospital. 
Their names were not released. Leung said two other Japanese were 
in stable condition. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane fell from 21,000 feet to 19,000 feet in about five to  
10 seconds, said Wang Guixiang, president and director of China's 
National Civil Aviation Corporation. 
</P>
<P>
	Some passengers said they saw others fly from their seats and  
hit the cabin's roof. 
</P>
<P>
	``It happened very suddenly and everything was very chaotic,''  
said Yau May Kam, a Taiwanese passenger whose 5-year-old daughter 
was slightly injured. ``The plane just dropped and I saw things 
flying all over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ambulances rushed the injured to three hospitals after the  
Boeing 757, with 160 passengers aboard, arrived at Chek Lap Kok 
airport from the southern Chinese city of Kunming, authorities 
said. About 10 people had to be carried off the plane on 
stretchers. 
</P>
<P>
	City civil aviation officials said the pilot didn't tell air  
traffic controllers of the air turbulence, and instead told his own 
airline -- but said only six people were hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Wang said the pilot was too busy trying to land the plane.  
</P>
<P>
	Southern Airlines officials were not immediately available for  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	In August, three people were killed when an MD-11 jet belonging  
to Taiwan's China Airlines crashed while landing in a storm at the 
airport. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
