<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hokies Prove They're No Fluke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLACKSBURG, Va. (AP) -- Who could blame the Hokies for bragging  
about this one? 
</P>
<P>
	In a setting where it has failed before, No. 4 Virginia Tech  
produced the biggest shutout ever of a team ranked in The 
Associated Press poll. 
</P>
<P>
	The 62-0 victory over Syracuse on Saturday may have provided  
irrefutable proof that the Hokies indeed belong in the national 
championship chase. 
</P>
<P>
	``We played with a lot of emotion in a big ball game against a  
good team,'' coach Frank Beamer said. ``We have the ability right 
now to get you in every way. I don't think we have a weakness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Hokies (6-0, 2-0 Big East) entered the game simply hoping  
they wouldn't blow it. They had started homecoming day unbeaten 
each of the last two years and were hit with big upsets both times. 
There was also the memory of a last-minute loss at Syracuse last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Well, they sure didn't blow it. Instead, it was a blowout  
against a team that came into the game ranked No. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was surprised,'' receiver Ricky Hall said. ``I hope it will  
erase all of the doubters, but that's not going to happen. You're 
still going to have doubters out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 63-year history of the AP poll, the previous record for  
biggest shutout of a ranked team was No. 1 Army's 61-0 victory over 
No. 6 Penn State in 1945. The largest losing margin for a ranked 
team is 63 points -- by No. 11 Texas in a 66-3 rout by UCLA two 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia Tech's defense led the way, scoring two touchdowns and  
allowing just three first downs before the backups came in at the 
start of the fourth quarter. The Orangemen gained 120 total yards, 
and the Hokies are now allowing an average of just 8 points per 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're playing great defense,'' Syracuse coach Paul  
Pasqualoni said. ``We made a play or two, but we were not able to 
consistently put plays together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But as much as the Hokies deserve credit for the lopsided  
victory, the Orangemen (5-2, 2-1) can blame themselves for the 
final, humiliating margin of defeat. Syracuse played ugly football 
in the second half, missing tackles, fumbling snaps and looking 
like a beaten team that just didn't care. 
</P>
<P>
	Pasqualoni was embarrassed. The loss was Syracuse's worst in 77  
years, and the Orangemen have been outscored 169-34 in their last 
four games at Lane Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things really got out of whack,'' Pasqualoni said. ``Life is  
90 percent how you react and 10 percent what happens. We have a lot 
of football to play. The No. 1 thing right now is the kids have to 
stay together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The score matched a 62-0 loss by the Orangemen at Princeton in  
1912. Syracuse was beaten 66-0 by Union in 1893 and 75-0 by Union 
in 1891. 
</P>
<P>
	For Virginia Tech, it was the largest margin of victory since a  
73-0 victory over Catholic in 1922. The 6-0 start is Tech's best 
since 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	Hokies freshman quarterback Michael Vick continued his quick  
maturation. He was 8-for-16 for 135 yards and one touchdown. In his 
last three games, Vick is 26-of-37 for 605 yards with six 
touchdowns and no interceptions -- and he is dancing out of the way 
of tacklers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vick gives them a dimension that is very special,'' Pasqualoni  
said. ``Even though he's only played in five or six games, he's 
throwing the ball with confidence. He's throwing and they're 
catching. He's elusive, kind of reminds you of (former Syracuse 
quarterbacks) Donovan McNabb or Marvin Graves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams have open dates next weekend, giving the Orangemen  
time to pull themselves together -- and the Hokies a little extra 
time to bask in the glow. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm proud of what we got going here,'' Beamer said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
