<DOCNO> APW19991017.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 12:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Dame Edna' Leaves Audiences Giddy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- There may be more theatrical sights on Broadway  
this season but for sheer blissful incongruity it will be hard to 
top a sea of gladioluses gracefully bobbing above contented, 
exhausted theatergoers at the Booth Theater. 
</P>
<P>
	Contented and exhausted because they have just laughed  
themselves silly over the antics of Dame Edna Everage, the creation 
and alter ego of Australian actor Barry Humphries. The performer 
has discovered there is gold in drag, particularly in England, 
where this exotic creature has flourished for more than two 
decades. Now, she's set to make her mark here. 
</P>
<P>
	The glads have been flung into the audience by Dame Edna at the  
end of her show, which opened Sunday at the Booth. It's called, 
appropriately enough ``Dame Edna: The Royal Tour.'' The Dame 
exhorts her fans -- possums, she calls them -- to thrust those 
flowers into the air and join her in a catchy little tune -- and 
they slavishly comply. 
</P>
<P>
	What does Dame Edna do exactly? Sing? More off-key than on.  
Dance? Ginger Rogers, she's not. Act? The woman is from the 
heaving-bosom-and-rolling-eyeball school of emoting. 
</P>
<P>
	What Dame Edna does better than anyone else is chat. She talks  
to the audience, bringing them into her gaudy world, a stage 
setting designed by Kenneth Foy that looks like a cross between a 
Las Vegas wedding chapel and Barbie's doll house. 
</P>
<P>
	Dame Edna herself could be Barbie's dizzy aunt, slightly naughty  
and not above a few catty remarks about everyone from Nicole Kidman 
to Dame Judi Dench. Her hair, purple cotton candy rather than 
coiffed, and her outfits -- check out the pink and silver shift in 
the first act -- celebrate excess. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Royal Tour'' is subtitled ``The Show that Listens,'' and  
Dame Edna does that, too. It is part of Humphries' genius that he 
works his conversations with audience members into an important 
part of the act. The results are sublimely funny, as the Dame 
tweaks herself and her willing victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Dame Edna has no doubts about her status as housewife, megastar,  
icon and adviser to the Queen of England. She dispenses wisdom with 
maternal pride, talking with theatergoers about their clothes, 
eating habits, decorating ability and their children. 
</P>
<P>
	Edna also talks about her family: unmarried son Kenny, a fashion  
designer with a penchant for leather and head of the Yvonne DeCarlo 
Appreciation Society, and daughter Valmai, who lives in one of New 
York's outer boroughs with her same-sex partner, a former tennis 
star of Eastern European descent. Then there is Edna's mother, who 
is spending her remaining days in ``a maximum security twilight 
home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Humphries gleefully attacks the cult of celebrity while having  
his creation revel in it. Dame Edna has no doubt about her worth. 
She cheerfully and publicly corrects flaws in others, but ``only in 
the nicest way possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Audience participation is a dangerous game, but Humphries gets  
the most out of eager theatergoers, turning innocuous facts he 
learns about them into belly laughs. He even parades a couple on 
stage to eat a meal and dresses up others as members of the Royal 
Family. 
</P>
<P>
	For all the supposed spontaneity of the evening, the show is  
carefully constructed. Humphries operates loosely with that 
structure, but he thinks fast and furiously enough to insure the 
laughs don't stop. ``Dame Edna: The Royal Tour'' makes for mighty 
entertainment -- but then, the woman, of course, is invincible. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
