<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scratch Pad Wins Alcibiades Stakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Racing with a substitute jockey on an  
unfamiliar track, Scratch Pad swept to a three-length victory 
Sunday in the $400,000 Alcibiades Stakes at Keeneland, earning a 
start in next month's Breeders' Cup Juvenile Fillies. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a tough trip for Scratch Pad, who had difficulties in the  
paddock and at the gate before settling in and racing to victory 
over eight other 2-year-old fillies. Rare Beauty was second and 
Cash Run third, another 6 1/2 lengths back. 
</P>
<P>
	Scratch Pad covered 1 1-16 miles on a fast track in 1:44.16.  
</P>
<P>
	Trainer Joseph Waunsch said Scratch Pad first acted up in the  
paddock and was taken back to her stall to be saddled. There, she 
threw herself over when she was startled by a flashbulb. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `There it goes,''' the trainer said afterward. ``There  
was no way. When they act stupid like that, they don't come back 
and run good. They take the race out of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To further complicate matters, jockey Willie Martinez had to  
back the filly out of the starting gate and dismount so her 
blinkers, which had come loose, could be changed by the starters. 
Again, she became fractious. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seemed like, for a moment, everything went against us,''  
Martinez said. ``That just shows you when a good horse is a good 
horse. ... Once she got into the race, she was good. She settled 
good. She's a big, long-strided filly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Settling into the middle of the pack, Scratch Pad went five-wide  
on the backstretch as she moved up, then edged toward the rail on 
the second turn as she closed in on Cash Run, the favorite and 
early pacesetter. 
</P>
<P>
	Scratch Pad took the lead at the top of the stretch and drew  
clear even as she drifted out. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner paid $12.60, $5.60 and $3, while Rare Beauty was  
$6.40 and $3.80, and Cash Run was $2.80 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez got his start as a jockey riding for Waunsch at Tampa  
Bay Downs a decade ago. He was a late substitute for Eibar Coa, who 
chose to remain at Miami's Calder Race Course, where Hurricane 
Irene had delayed several races from Friday and Saturday to Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was on a lot of favorites and Coa wants to be the leading  
rider. He's three wins in front, and he wants to stay that way,'' 
Waunsch said. ``So I guess it was more important to him to be a 
leading rider than to possibly ride a Breeders' Cup winner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After running all four of her previous starts at Calder, Waunsch  
said Scratch Pad probably would have stayed there and run in the 
Florida Stallion Series for 2-year-old fillies -- if breeder Tim 
Ahearn hadn't missed a $50 nomination payment. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is great,'' he said. ``I'm not complaining. I'm glad we  
came.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The way Scratch Pad handled the Alcibiades field, Waunsch said  
he was confident she can take on other top contenders like Darling 
My Darling and unbeaten Chilukki at the Nov. 6 Breeders' Cup at 
Gulfstream. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe she'll only win by a length, but that'll be good enough  
for me,'' he said with a laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	In an earlier stakes, the $100,000 Thoroughbred Club of America,  
Bourbon Belle outdueled Cinemine down the stretch of the 
six-furlong sprint for older fillies and mares, only to be placed 
second when stewards ruled jockey Patrick Johnson interfered with 
Cinemine. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
