<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Auctions Cattle on Video </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEDELLIN, Colombia (AP) -- Contestants parade before the admiring  
gazes of the all-male audience while the master of ceremonies reads 
off the contenders' full-bodied measurements. 
</P>
<P>
	``Check out those beauties,'' exclaims Arturo Jaraba, the  
evening's host at the video cattle auction in an air-conditioned 
conference center in the capital of war-wracked Antioquia state. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at the way they walk,'' he beams.  
</P>
<P>
	Popularized a decade ago in the United States as a low-cost way  
to unite distant buyers and sellers, the auctioning of cattle 
videotaped on faraway ranches is catching on in Colombia for an 
even more compelling reason. 
</P>
<P>
	The gatherings in safe urban venues allow ranchers to do  
business without venturing personally into Colombia's lawless 
countryside,where they are coveted kidnap targets for leftist 
rebels trying to finance their 35-year-old struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	The auctions have also become social events. The ranchers swap  
stories, whisper secrets, tell jokes and sip aguardiente, a 
traditional licorice-flavored liqueur served by cheerful 
waitresses. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been my savior,'' said Javier Builes, a burly  
57-year-old cattleman who has sold hundreds of heads of cattle at 
the events, which began in Medellin in March and have extended to 
four other cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Builes said he's narrowly escaped three abduction attempts,  
although other family members have fallen prey. A nephew was freed 
in September after seven months held captive by Colombia's largest 
rebel band, the leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or 
FARC. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cattle ranchers are the most ravaged of the industries,'' said  
Juan Mesa, who directs the private Pais Libre anti-kidnapping 
foundation. ``They are immensely vulnerable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 10 percent of the victims of the nearly 2,000 abductions  
reported annually in Colombia are cattlemen, snared by guerrillas, 
common criminals and right-wing militias who are the rebels' main 
rivals, Mesa said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who do roam their lands unmolested have typically  
``vaccinated'' themselves by making sizable payoffs to the rebels. 
Between 1997 and 1998 cattlemen shelled out $131 million in 
extortion payments, according to the National Cattle Ranchers 
Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	The insecurity, says the federation, is taking a devastating  
toll in Latin America's third-ranking cattle industry, one that 
employs some 300,000 people and is an integral part of the national 
folklore. 
</P>
<P>
	Although many cattle buyers will still only purchase an animal  
they can inspect firsthand, the video auction trend is catching on 
with a total of 16,000 animals sold, said Jarabe, the auctioneer 
who has pioneered the practice in Colombia. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the security factor, many ranchers are learning they can  
avoid the costs of transporting their cattle to the auctions, long 
trips in which the cows often arrive underweight after days without 
eating. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to each video auction, Jaraba's firm sends crews out to  
film the cattle on the absentee owners' ranches, which are 
typically run by local hired hands. 
</P>
<P>
	One sunny afternoon on a ranch in Monteria, a town 170 miles  
north of Medellin, company employee Carmelo Carcamo jotted down the 
weight, color, and ages of a dozen hunchbacked Brahman cattle. With 
a portable video camera he then filmed the animals striding in a 
pack along a dung-strewn corral beside a vast green pasture. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's simple,'' said Carcamo, who visits as many as 15 ranches  
in a day in the region. ``You choose them, weigh them, mark them, 
and film them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the kidnapping risk running higher than ever as Colombia's  
insurgency escalates, many ranchers have stopped going to their 
properties altogether. 
</P>
<P>
	But an intrepid few can't stay away.  
</P>
<P>
	Saying he has ranching in his blood, Builes still travels  
occasionally to his 360-acre property in northern Sucre state, a 
battleground for the rebels and rightist paramilitary groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``I go, but I don't stay long,'' he said smiling broadly.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
