<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penn State Stifles Buckeyes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- The situation was strangely similar to  
the game-turning play of last year's showdown between Ohio State 
and Penn State. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Nittany Lions pinned deep in their territory, the  
Buckeyes sacked Kevin Thompson, forced a fumble, leapt on it for 
the touchdown and grabbed the momentum. 
</P>
<P>
	After that turn of events last October, the Lions quickly  
surrendered. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, they didn't.  
</P>
<P>
	Unfazed, they went on to win 23-10, proving the point they've  
been trying to make all year: This isn't the same team that folded 
against Top 25 teams the past two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember someone on the sideline saying, `We are not going  
to fall apart. We're a different team,''' said Penn State defensive 
lineman Justin Kurpeikis. 
</P>
<P>
	As their march toward the national title continues, No. 2 Penn  
State (7-0, 3-0 Big Ten) had better hope they're different than the 
last Lions team to start 7-0. In 1997, that group collapsed at the 
end to finish 9-3. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitfalls are possible: No. 16 Purdue is next, and No. 24  
Minnesota, No. 9 Michigan and No. 11 Michigan State await in 
November. 
</P>
<P>
	There's good news for these Lions: They have a stifling defense  
the 1997 Penn State team lacked. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made our minds up that we have to win a couple of these  
kind of games,'' coach Joe Paterno said. ``The defense came to 
town. Really, it would be tough to think they've played a better 
one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State managed 71 yards in the first half and 72 in the  
second, and the 143 yards of total offense was the least Penn State 
has surrendered since joining the Big Ten in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	An offense averaging 399 yards per game got only 11 first downs  
and never found the end zone. Ohio State dropped to 4-3 overall, 
1-2 in the conference and No. 22 in the AP poll. 
</P>
<P>
	``You only get four against Ohio State. After what they've done  
to us, last year, and how they ruined a few seasons since I've been 
here, it feels great,'' Kurpeikis said, recalling losses to Ohio 
State in 1996 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State's victory started with blitzes. The Lions finished  
with eight sacks on Buckeyes quarterback Steve Bellisari. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a big concern -- that he's back there taking so many  
beatings,'' said Ohio State receiver Reggie Germany. ``We just 
didn't have a lot of time today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It got worse after the Buckeyes' defensive score pulled them  
within 13-10 at the end of the first half and threatened a repeat 
of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no deja vu here,'' Lions linebacker Brandon Short told  
the team in the huddle. 
</P>
<P>
	He was right. Penn State's defense forced the Buckeyes to go  
three-and-out on their first three series of the second half. On 
the fourth series, James Boyd intercepted Bellisari. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're as good or better than advertised,'' Ohio State's John  
Cooper said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
