<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Group Seeks Hispanic Backers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- No mas. No more, says Scott Reed -- a  
Republican presidential consultant tired of watching GOP 
politicians drive Hispanic voters to the Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	So the strategist who managed Bob Dole's failed 1996  
presidential bid is launching a campaign of his own for 2000. The 
goal: show Republicans how to attract Hispanics. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't leave this ground unattended,'' Reed said.  
</P>
<P>
	His new organization, the Republican Leadership Coalition, is  
spending $45,000 on radio ads on Hispanic stations in Florida, 
California, New Mexico and Texas. The spots, produced in Spanish, 
promote a Republican congressional plan that would give tax credits 
of up to $3,000 to insurance companies that provide policies to the 
uninsured. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fair-Care gives $3,000 a year, tax-free, so that every family  
can buy health insurance,'' an announcer says in the ads, which 
begin airing this week. ``With this, you can buy health insurance 
with any private company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The coalition is pretty much a one-man operation that raises  
money to pay for political research and advertising focused on 
Hispanic voters. Reed hired a pollster to interview small groups of 
Hispanics to determine what issues most interest them. 
</P>
<P>
	Health care ``was off the charts,'' he said. Many of the  
Hispanics from California and Texas said they go to Mexico to get 
medical care. 
</P>
<P>
	Education, another top concern raised in the focus groups, will  
be the subject of the next batch of ads, Reed said. He plans 
follow-up research to document any effects the ads had on Hispanic 
listeners. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed is trying to bring Hispanics into the GOP with the ads, but  
his broader goal is to demonstrate to Republican leaders that the 
right message can draw voters from the nation's fastest-growing 
population bloc. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're committed to expanding the Republican majority coalition  
and we recognized the increasingly important role that minorities 
play with all these changing demographic trends at the national, 
state and local levels,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have alienated Hispanics with anti-immigration  
policies and rhetoric that makes them feel unwanted, Reed said. He 
eventually hopes to extend his effort to blacks and other 
minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think if you look at the results of the elections in  
California last year, where we lost two statewide elections by huge 
margins and left the Republican Party in shambles, the answer is 
yes. We've hurt ourselves with Hispanics,'' he said. ``And if we 
don't do something about this and go back to talking about issues 
that people can understand we will become the minority party 
overnight.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
