<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stopping Dallas Starts With Emmitt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- The New York Giants' defensive unit  
has enough to wonder about. Such as when the offense will start 
scoring. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the defense has something else to ponder -- the rejuvenation  
of Emmitt Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas running back comes into Monday's night's game against  
the New York Giants leading the NFC in rushing with 409 yards. He 
also is tied for second overall in the league, just 14 yards behind 
Corey Dillon of the Cincinnati Bengals. 
</P>
<P>
	While Giants defensive line coach Denny Marcin has been in the  
league only three years, he insists Smith has gotten better the 
last few years. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first year we played them, I said: `Man, that's not the  
Emmitt Smith I saw on TV,'' the longtime college coach said. ``Last 
year, he turned it up and this year, to me, he looks like the best 
I've seen him. He's running hard, getting to the outside and making 
good cuts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With receiver Michael Irvin sidelined indefinitely with a spinal  
injury, the Cowboys may need even more from Smith. He enters the 
game 25 yards shy of becoming the fourth NFL player to rush for 
13,000 yards in his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have confidence in the guys that are going to be in there,''  
Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said. ``But at the same time, anytime you 
lose a player of Michael's stature you lose something off your 
football team. It will have an impact. How much of an impact, 
remains to be seen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even if Irvin were playing, the Giants' approach would be to  
stop Smith first. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not one-dimensional,'' safety Percy Ellsworth said.  
``We can hold Emmitt to 60-some-odd yards and still lose because 
Troy (Aikman) can throw for 300. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we have to at least get them to the point where we know  
they will pass and then see how we match up,'' Ellsworth added. 
``We're a solid group in the secondary, so if we can stop the run 
and force them to pass, we should have some success.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's not always been the case. In the last six games against  
the Giants, Smith has carried 103 times for 415 yards and two 
touchdowns. That's a 69.2-yard average, 4.0 per carry. 
</P>
<P>
	What's even more interesting is that in Dallas' 16-6 win over  
the Giants last Nov. 8, Smith rushed for 163 yards. That means in 
the other five games against New York, he had only 252 yards 
combined, or 50 yards on average. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that we will allow Michael's injury to determine  
how we are going to approach the game offensively,'' Aikman said. 
``That is really the way we have done it for quite some time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the Cowboys' 31-7 win at Giants Stadium on a Monday night  
early last season, Deion Sanders scored on a punt return and an 
interception return. He also set up another TD with a 55-yard pass 
reception. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're still good,'' Giants All Pro defensive end Michael  
Strahan said. ``They're better with Michael Irvin, don't get me 
wrong. But without him, they are still a good offense. The key is 
stopping the running game and, with Dallas, that means Emmitt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, the Giants have struggled all season  
offensively, whether it's been with Kent Graham or Kerry Collins at 
quarterback. Graham will be back this week after missing last 
week's 14-3 loss to Arizona because of a concussion. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss triggered an offense vs. defense tiff for a day or so,  
but that dispute has subsided, for now. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to win for the morale of the team,'' kicker Brad  
Daluiso said. ``That would help a lot. To get a win on national 
television against the Cowboys, it would do a lot for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But here's a bad statistic for Giants: Dallas is 6-0 in Monday  
night games against New York. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
