<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 15:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brunell Leaves With Bruised Ribs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Jacksonville Jaguars quarterback Mark  
Brunell left Sunday's game against the Cleveland Browns in the 
third quarter with bruised ribs. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Tom Coughlin said Brunell took the first blow to the ribs  
sometime in the first half, then was knocked out of the game when 
he strained the ribs making a long throw down the sideline to start 
the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Brunell returned to the sideline and threw for a brief period,  
but Coughlin said there was no way the quarterback would return to 
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had difficulty twisting and turning and throwing the  
ball,'' Coughlin said. ``So we made the decision not to put him 
in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coughlin said he didn't yet know how serious the injury was.  
Brunell will have the luxury of the bye week as he begins his 
recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jaguars also have the comfort of knowing that, yet again,  
they have a dependable backup quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay Fiedler led three scoring drives and finished 12-for-14 for  
113 yards and one touchdown in the 24-7 victory. He followed in the 
footsteps of other backups who have thrived for the Jaguars, 
including Rob Johnson, Steve Matthews and Jamie Martin, who is now 
a third-stringer for the Browns. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been fortunate that we've had some young men who have  
been able to accomplish that, knowing full well they're not the 
starter, but having to understand everything,'' Coughlin said. ``He 
knew the game plan and he responded well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fiedler left the field with the fans chanting his name.  
</P>
<P>
	Undoubtedly, his solid performance will stir something of a  
quarterback controversy. Brunell entered the game with a 72.0 
quarterback rating and was struggling along with the rest of the 
Jaguars offense, which was ranked 20th in the league in passing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mark is out starter right now,'' Fiedler said. ``Until coach  
Coughlin makes a change, that's the way it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coughlin said no change was imminent.  
</P>
<P>
	``Mark's the starter and Jay's the second quarterback and that's  
how it is,'' Coughlin said. ``It's not going to change.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
