<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strike Threat Looms for GM Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The Canadian Auto Workers will strike General  
Motors Corp. this week unless the company withdraws its proposal to 
outsource hundreds of jobs at five plants, union President Buzz 
Hargrove said. 
</P>
<P>
	The union's strike deadline is midnight Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	The automaker has reduced the number of jobs it wants to  
eliminate by shifting them to outside suppliers from more than 
1,000 to about 700, Hargrove said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said the CAW will not accept any outsourcing at a time  
when more than 1,500 workers are on layoff from GM's Canadian 
plants. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is not a chance we will agree to these outsourcing  
decisions,'' Hargrove told reporters at a news conference in 
Toronto. Unless GM withdraws the proposal, ``we'll have a strike,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stew Low, a spokesman for GM Canada, said the outsourcing is one  
of the issues still on the table. He said GM's investment plan 
``may require a minor degree of outsourcing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During 1996 contract talks, the CAW struck GM's Oshawa, Ontario,  
assembly plant, idling some U.S. parts and assembly plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Other aspects of the contract with GM are expected to closely  
model agreements already reached with Ford Motor Co. and 
DaimlerChrysler AG. 
</P>
<P>
	Those call for a 3 percent wage increase in each year of a  
three-year package, a $1,000 (Canadian) signing bonus, an improved 
retirement package and other benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Hargrove said in July that the future of the St. Therese,  
Ontario, plant and GM plans to outsource work would be key issues 
in this year's negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	GM has said it will cease production of Chevrolet Cameros and  
Pontiac Firebirds at St. Therese in September 2002, and nothing is 
scheduled to replace that line, Hargrove said. 
</P>
<P>
	The union is willing to consider modular assembly proposals for  
St. Therese as part of a plan to keep the plant open, Hargrove 
said. Modular assembly involves suppliers assembling many 
components into modules -- such as a complete dashboard -- that are 
then put into the vehicle at assembly plants. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, GM has not budged on its plan to close the plant, he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A strike would be expected to have some effect on U.S. plants  
that provide parts for GM's Canadian assembly plants and on U.S. 
assembly plants that use parts made by GM in Canada. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
