<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Oct. 17, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	N.C. Issues Flash Flood Warning  
</P>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, N.C. (AP) -- A flash flood warning was issued for a  
100-mile-by-50-mile swath of eastern North Carolina straddling 
Interstate 95 between Fayetteville and Rocky Mount as Hurricane 
Irene drenched the state in the southeast with nearly half a foot 
of rain today. Gale-force winds were measured at the coast, and a 
tornado was reported by radar over Jacksonville on Sunday morning. 
No injuries were reported. At 8 p.m. EDT, Irene was located near 
latitude 33.3 north and longitude 77.8 west. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Nurse Convicted in 6 Ind. Deaths  
</P>
<P>
	BRAZIL, Ind. (AP) -- A former nurse was convicted of murder today  
in the deaths of six patients who authorities said were 
deliberately given lethal injections at a western Indiana hospital. 
Jurors hearing the case of Orville Lynn Majors told the judge they 
could not reach a verdict on the seventh count. Majors, 38, faces a 
maximum of 65 years in prison on each count. The judge set 
sentencing for Nov. 15. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Has Mixed Reaction to Pakistan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States today praised Gen. Pervaiz  
Musharraf for pledging to return Pakistan to democratic rule but 
expressed disappointment that the military leader offered no 
timetable for that transition. U.S. officials said they were 
pleased by several points Musharraf made in an address Sunday, his 
first public appearance since announcing last week that he had 
ousted Pakistan's civilian government. They cited his references to 
reducing the military presence at the border with India. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Minority Students Lag Among Wealthy  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Black and Hispanic students lag behind white and  
Asian students academically -- even when they come from similarly 
privileged backgrounds, according to a new report. To bridge the 
gap, the report issued today by the College Board recommends 
tutoring, mentoring and other support to minority students in all 
grades and from all socioeconomic backgrounds. Some experts cited 
racism and peer pressure as reasons behind performance differences. 

</P>
<P>
	Chechen Leader Calls for Talks  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian artillery and warplanes pressed  
their attacks around Chechnya's capital Sunday, while the 
republic's president called for urgent negotiations to end the 
fighting. The Russian commander in Chechnya, Col. Gen. Viktor 
Kazantsev, said Sunday his forces had taken a strategic ridge 20 
miles northwest of Grozny, south of the Terek River that cuts 
across the northern third of Chechnya. Chechen President Aslan 
Maskhadov called for talks, despite the Kremlin's earlier refusals. 

</P>
<P>
	Sheppard's Son Ends 400-Mile Walk  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The son of Dr. Sam Sheppard completed a  
400-mile walk on Sunday that he started a month ago with the aim of 
preparing himself for trial of his wrongful imprisonment lawsuit 
against the state of Ohio. Dr. Sheppard spent a decade in jail for 
the 1954 beating death of his wife, Marilyn, before a second jury 
acquitted him in a retrial. The sensational trial inspired a movie 
and ``The Fugitive'' television series. His son, Sam Reese 
Sheppard, has been trying to clear his father's name and hold state 
officials responsible for what he calls a miscarriage of justice. 

</P>
<P>
	Fedex Plane Misses Runway in Philippines  
</P>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- A Federal Express cargo plane  
overshot the runway and ran into the ocean while landing at an 
airport northwest of Manila, but both pilots escaped with minor 
injuries, officials said Monday. The MD-11 plane, which originated 
in Shanghai, was landing at Subic freeport shortly before midnight 
Sunday when it overshot the runway, said Bong Meneses, an official 
of the national Air Transportation Office. Fedex said most of the 
plane's cargo had been damaged ``and may not be salvageable.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell broadly in early trading after  
last week's sell-off on Wall Street. The benchmark Nikkei shed 
189.58 points to 17,411.99 in early trading Monday. On Friday, the 
Dow lost 266.90 points, or 2.6 percent, to close at 10,019.71. 

</P>
<P>
	Mets Beat Braves 4-3 in 15 Innings  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) --Robin Ventura's grand slam-turned-single drove  
home the winning run in the 15th inning and gave the New York Mets 
a 4-3 victory over the Atlanta Braves in Game 5 of the NL 
championship series, the longest postseason contest in baseball 
history. The 5-hour, 46-minute game ended in total confusion, three 
runners crossing the plate while Ventura was mobbed by his 
teammates before he could get to second base. The Mets forced a 
Game 6 in Atlanta on Tuesday night. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KELLY GRUEL  
  	   	
