<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eagles 20, Bears 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- It took a career half from Doug Pederson to give  
the Philadelphia Eagles their first win in 20 road games since Dec. 
14, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Pederson, playing like another quarterback Eagles coach Andy  
Reid tutored in Green Bay, had career highs in completions (16), 
yards passing (207) and longest pass (57 yards) by halftime Sunday, 
and the Eagles hung on for the 20-16 victory over the Chicago 
Bears. 
</P>
<P>
	Cade McNown, making his first NFL start in place of the injured  
Shane Matthews, threw an 80-yard touchdown pass, and Chris Boniol 
kicked a 41-yard field goal in the second half, but the Bears (3-3) 
came up empty in two other trips inside the Eagles 31. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory gives Philadelphia (2-4), which beat Dallas last  
week, a winning streak for the first time since 1997. It also is 
the Eagles' first victory ever at Soldier Field, and just their 
second win over Chicago since 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia, 0-18-1 since beating the New York Jets 21-20  
almost three years ago, looked right at home in the first half. 
After going three-and-out on their first series, the Eagles scored 
on their next four possessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Everything seemed to go their way, with the second series  
symbolizing the half. After two Eagles were called for pass 
interference, giving them second-and-20 from their own 36, Pederson 
hit Torrance Small for a 7-yard gain. 
</P>
<P>
	On the next play, Pederson and Dietrich Jells connected for a  
57-yard score, the Eagles' longest play from scrimmage this season. 
It also was a career-long for Pederson, topping his 36-yard pass to 
Charles Johnson last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Pederson also threw a 3-yard TD pass to Luther Broughton, and  
Norm Johnson kicked field goals of 28 and 27 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Pederson finished 32-of-38 for 228 yards. Duce Staley rushed for  
101 yards on 23 carries. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears, who had fans talking playoffs after upsetting the  
Minnesota Vikings at the Metrodome last weekend, reverted to their 
bumbling ways of last year. The defense was practically helpless in 
the first half and the offense was out of synch all game. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago fans had no idea when the season began how much they'd  
miss Matthews. Though McNown played at least one series in each of 
the first five games, he looked shaky in his first start. 
</P>
<P>
	He threw two interceptions in the first half, with the first  
setting up a Philadelphia field goal. It didn't help that he was 
playing without leading receiver Curtis Conway, who was out with a 
sprained ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	He looked sharper in the second half, finding Marcus Robinson  
for the 80-yard score on his second play of the third quarter. But 
he couldn't find the end zone again, getting sacked for a loss at 
the Eagles 31 and throwing an incompletion on fourth-and-3 from the 
Eagles 30. 
</P>
<P>
	McNown finished 17-of-33 for 255 yards.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
