<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yonehara Wins Athens Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Japan's Masato Yonehara sprinted to the  
finish line and defeated last year's winner, Nikos Pollias, by 
three seconds to win the Athens Marathon Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 32-year-old Yonehara finished in a time of 2 hours, 18  
minutes and 35 seconds. Pollias' countryman Vassilis Zambelis, of 
Greece, was third at 2:22:29. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very stressful... but I'm very happy,'' said Yonehara,  
winner of the 1994 Portland Marathon. ``The course was difficult, a 
lot of uphill and downhill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the women's field, Okuno Tamaki of Japan won in 2:46:46,  
beating Greece's Georgia Abatzidou and Iota Nikolakopoulou, who 
finished respectively in 2:53:01 and 3:09:13. 
</P>
<P>
	The same course is planned for the 2004 Olympics in Athens.  
</P>
<P>
	Organizers said more than 1,500 people took part in the  
marathon, which ended at the all-marble Pan Athenian stadium, site 
of the first modern Olympic Games in 1896. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
