<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NiSource Raises Columbia Energy Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HERNDON, Va. (AP) -- NiSource Inc. has upped its offer for  
Columbia Energy Group by 9 percent, or $6 a share, to try to 
persuade Columbia to drop its vigorous, months-long efforts to fend 
off the bid. 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource, facing a deadline today to announce the results of a  
$68 a share offer initially made in June, said Sunday it would pay 
$74 a share for the Virginia company. The increase would boost the 
value of the deal to $6.1 billion from $5.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The sweetened bid offers shareholders a 22 percent premium over  
Columbia's Friday's closing price of $60.50 on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's offer is the right price for the right company at the  
right time,'' said Gary L. Neale, NiSource's chairman, president 
and chief executive officer. ``The $74 cash per share we are 
offering is well above the value that Columbia, on its own, in any 
reasonable time frame, could provide its shareholders and allows 
Columbia shareholders to receive their share of the value created 
by the combination of the two companies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The offer expires at midnight Nov. 12.  
</P>
<P>
	In an overture to Columbia's management, Neale said Columbia  
Energy Chairman Oliver G. Richard III would become vice chairman of 
the combined company, and that he and four other members of 
Columbia's board would be invited to join an expanded NiSource 
board. 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource, based in Merrillville, Ind., said its bid has received  
``substantial'' support from Columbia shareholders, with 44.4 
million shares, or nearly 54 percent, agreeing to the offer, as of 
midnight Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement Sunday, Columbia Energy said its board would  
review the higher offer but urged shareholders not to act before 
the board had made a recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	Maria Hibbs, a spokeswoman for NiSource, said size and geography  
are becoming increasingly critical to succeeding in the changing 
energy industry. She said NiSource and Columbia Energy would make a 
good fit in a natural gas distribution corridor stretching from the 
Chicago market to New England. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Columbia launched a final appeal to shareholders to  
reject the previous NiSource bid. The Herndon-based company also 
paid for ads in Indiana newspapers claiming that the buyout would 
harm consumers there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shouldn't NiSource be spending its time and money trying to  
reduce harmful smokestack emissions and protecting the welfare of 
its customers and communities in Indiana?'' said one ad, which 
accused NiSource of having a ``disturbing environmental record.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource is the parent company of Northern Indiana Public  
Service Co. and Bay State Gas Co. in Massachusetts. It would become 
one of the nation's biggest natural gas companies if the takeover 
succeeds. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy is involved in natural gas exploration,  
production, transmission, storage and distribution as well as 
propane sales and electric power generation, sales and trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Columbia Energy attempted to buy Pittsburgh-based  
Consolidated Natural Gas. But CNG rejected the offer and chose to 
proceed with a previously planned merger with Richmond, Va.-based 
Dominion Resources Inc. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991017.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 18:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Lots of quarterback changes brought mixed results.  
</P>
<P>
	For Jacksonville, Miami and Detroit, the changes worked. For the  
Jets, Vikings, Bears and Saints, they didn't. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay Fiedler, a fourth-year veteran from Dartmouth, replaced the  
injured Mark Brunell and led the sputtering Jaguars to 18 points 
over the final 1 1/2 quarters Sunday, going 12-of-14 for 113 yards and 
scrambling three times for 27 yards in a 24-7 victory over the 
Cleveland Browns. 
</P>
<P>
	Damon Huard, filling in after Dan Marino left early with a sore  
shoulder, threw a 5-yard touchdown pass to Stanley Pritchett with 
23 seconds left to give the Dolphins a 31-30 win over the New 
England Patriots. 
</P>
<P>
	Gus Frerotte relieved the injured Charlie Batch for Detroit and  
had five straight completions for 45 yards to set up Jason Hanson's 
winning field goal in a 25-23 victory over Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	In other games Sunday, Indianapolis edged the Jets 16-13;  
Philadelphia topped Chicago 20-16; Tennessee downed New Orleans 
24-21; Oakland defeated Buffalo 20-14; Pittsburgh beat Cincinnati 
17-13; St. Louis crushed Atlanta 41-13; San Diego edged Seattle 
13-10; Denver downed Green Bay 31-10; and Carolina nipped San 
Francisco 31-29. 
</P>
<P>
	In a night game, it was Washington at Arizona.  
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore, Kansas City and Tampa Bay had the week off.  
</P>
<P>
	Brunell appeared to injure his ribs early in the third quarter  
when he threw a long pass down the sideline that Jimmy Smith just 
missed. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacksonville (5-1) trailed 7-6 when linebacker Bryan Schwartz  
forced a fumble that was recovered by Kevin Hardy at the 25-yard 
line of the Browns (0-6). 
</P>
<P>
	Three plays later, Fiedler lobbed a pass to the corner of the  
end zone to Kyle Brady, who extended for a nice catch in double 
coverage and a 7-yard touchdown -- the first TD pass of Fiedler's 
career. A 2-point conversion made it 14-7. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time a starting quarterback gets hurt and comes out,  
everyone else picks his game up a little bit,'' Fiedler said. 
``They helped me out a great deal. The line was protecting very 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Jacksonville forced a punt, Fiedler directed the best  
drive of the day, a 70-yard march that included completions to 
three receivers and ended with a 2-yard touchdown run by James 
Stewart for a 21-7 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	As the Jaguars left the field, fans serenaded Brunell's  
replacement with chants of ``Fiedler, Fiedler, Fiedler.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Within minutes, coach Tom Coughlin was answering questions about  
who the starter would be once Jacksonville returns from a bye week, 
assuming Brunell recovers from the bruised ribs that sidelined him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our situation will not change,'' Coughlin said. ``Hopefully,  
Mark will be able to rest this week and he'll be ready to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
                      *Dolphins 31, Patriots 30    	
</P>
<P>
	At Foxboro, Mass., the Dolphins had fallen behind 14-0 on two  
interception returns by the Patriots (4-2) -- a 57-yarder by Andy 
Katzenmoyer off Marino and a 24-yarder by Ty Law on Huard's first 
pass. 
</P>
<P>
	But after that Huard settled down. He threw a 69-yard TD pass to  
Tony Martin and the final 5-yard score to Pritchett on a 59-yard 
drive on which he converted three third downs -- a third-and-10, a 
third-and-9 and a third-and-5. He finished 24-of-42 for 240 yards 
and ran six times for 54 times. 
</P>
<P>
	In between, Olindo Mare kept Miami (4-1) in the game with six  
field goals -- breaking an NFL record by kicking four or more for 
the fourth straight game. They included a 53-yarder with 3:01 left 
that set the stage for Miami's final drive. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Lions 25, Vikings 23    	
</P>
<P>
	At Pontiac, Mich., Hanson's 47-yard field goal put Detroit on  
top 22-20 with 7:06 remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff George, who replaced the ineffective Randall Cunningham,  
had a 38-yard completion to Jake Reed in a 71-yard drive that set 
up Gary Anderson's 26-yarder to give Minnesota (2-4) a 23-22 lead. 
Still, some of the Vikings felt they should have gone for a 
touchdown instead of settling for that field goal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted a touchdown,'' said Randy Moss, who had 10 receptions  
for 125 yards. ``Last year's team went for everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the winning field goal, Hanson was good from 43 yards out,  
but officials waved it off, flagging the Lions (3-2) for delay. 
Then the Vikings called a timeout in an effort to test Hanson's 
nerves before he hit the winner. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Colts 17, Jets 14    	
</P>
<P>
	At East Rutherford, N.J., untested Ray Lucas made his first NFL  
start and threw a late interception at the goal line that Jeff 
Burris returned 55 yards. The runback set up Mike Vanderjagt's 
27-yard field goal with 14 seconds remaining to give the Colts 
(3-2) the win. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were on the sideline talking about our two-minute drill,''  
Colts quarterback Peyton Manning said. ``We were hoping to be down 
by only three, but expecting to be down by seven. Fortunately, Jeff 
and the defense put us in position to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets (1-5) blew an early 13-0 lead.  
</P>
<P>
                         *Eagles 20, Bears 16    	
</P>
<P>
	At Chicago, Doug Pederson had career highs in completions (16),  
yards passing (207) and longest pass (57 yards) by halftime, and 
the Eagles (2-4) hung on for the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Cade McNown, making his first NFL start in place of the injured  
Shane Matthews, threw an 80-yard touchdown pass, and Chris Boniol 
kicked a 41-yard field goal in the second half, but the Bears (3-3) 
came up empty in two trips to the Eagles 31. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Titans 24, Saints 21    	
</P>
<P>
	At New Orleans, the Titans (5-1) rallied to win in the second  
half for the fourth time this season, while the Saints (1-4) lost a 
second-half lead for the fourth straight game. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Fisk, a 300-pound defensive tackle, and cornerback Donald  
Mitchell intercepted passes in the closing minutes to secure the 
outcome as the Titans continued their best start since 1991, when 
they opened 7-1 as the Houston Oilers. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Raiders 20, Bills 14    	
</P>
<P>
	At Buffalo, Eric Turner picked off Doug Flutie's 24-yard  
desperation pass in the end zone with no time left. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyrone Wheatley had 97 of his team's 195 yards rushing and  
scored two touchdowns, and Michael Husted kicked two field goals as 
Oakland (3-3) snapped the four-game winning streak that Buffalo 
(4-2) brought into the game. 
</P>
<P>
                       *Steelers 17, Bengals 3    	
</P>
<P>
	At Cincinnati, Jerome Bettis bowled over tacklers and provided  
the only semblance of offense by either team, rushing for 111 yards 
and two touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers (3-3) intercepted Cincinnati (1-5) quarterback  
Akili Smith twice, sacked him four times, batted down four throws 
at the line and got their hands on 13 of his throws overall. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Rams 41, Falcons 13    	
</P>
<P>
	At Atlanta, Tony Horne had a 101-yard kickoff return and Grant  
Wistrom brought back an interception 91 yards for a score as St. 
Louis (5-0) remained the league's only undefeated team. 
</P>
<P>
	Kurt Warner engineered touchdown drives on the first two  
possessions, and after the Falcons (1-5) cut the lead to 14-7 early 
in the second, Horne raced down the sideline for his second scoring 
kickoff return in two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
                      *Chargers 13, Seahawks 10    	
</P>
<P>
	At San Diego, John Carney kicked two field goals over the final  
2:54, including the game-winning 41-yarder as time expired. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chargers, under rookie head coach Mike Riley, improved to  
4-1 for the first time since 1996. The Seahawks, in their first 
year under Mike Holmgren, fell to 3-2. 
</P>
<P>
                       *Broncos 31, Packers 10    	
</P>
<P>
	At Denver, Brian Griese threw two touchdown passes to Ed  
McCaffrey and ran for a third and the Broncos (2-4) finished with a 
huge edge in total offense (514-133) and time of possession 
(45:14-14:46). 
</P>
<P>
	Olandis Gary, elevated to a starting role because of injuries to  
Terrell Davis and Derek Loville, carried 37 times for 124 yards and 
a score, and the Broncos' defense intercepted Brett Favre three 
times. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Panthers 31, 49ers 29    	
</P>
<P>
	At San Francisco, the Panthers (2-3) scored 24 second-quarter  
points and hung on to stop San Francisco's club-record 19-game home 
winning streak. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Beuerlein threw for four touchdowns, including 7- and  
33-yard strikes to Patrick Jeffers. The 49ers (3-3) played their 
third straight game without Steve Young, still bothered by the 
aftereffects of his fourth concussion in three years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
