<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Dame Edna' Leaves Audiences Giddy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- There may be more theatrical sights on Broadway  
this season but for sheer blissful incongruity it will be hard to 
top a sea of gladioluses gracefully bobbing above contented, 
exhausted theatergoers at the Booth Theater. 
</P>
<P>
	Contented and exhausted because they have just laughed  
themselves silly over the antics of Dame Edna Everage, the creation 
and alter ego of Australian actor Barry Humphries. The performer 
has discovered there is gold in drag, particularly in England, 
where this exotic creature has flourished for more than two 
decades. Now, she's set to make her mark here. 
</P>
<P>
	The glads have been flung into the audience by Dame Edna at the  
end of her show, which opened Sunday at the Booth. It's called, 
appropriately enough ``Dame Edna: The Royal Tour.'' The Dame 
exhorts her fans -- possums, she calls them -- to thrust those 
flowers into the air and join her in a catchy little tune -- and 
they slavishly comply. 
</P>
<P>
	What does Dame Edna do exactly? Sing? More off-key than on.  
Dance? Ginger Rogers, she's not. Act? The woman is from the 
heaving-bosom-and-rolling-eyeball school of emoting. 
</P>
<P>
	What Dame Edna does better than anyone else is chat. She talks  
to the audience, bringing them into her gaudy world, a stage 
setting designed by Kenneth Foy that looks like a cross between a 
Las Vegas wedding chapel and Barbie's doll house. 
</P>
<P>
	Dame Edna herself could be Barbie's dizzy aunt, slightly naughty  
and not above a few catty remarks about everyone from Nicole Kidman 
to Dame Judi Dench. Her hair, purple cotton candy rather than 
coiffed, and her outfits -- check out the pink and silver shift in 
the first act -- celebrate excess. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Royal Tour'' is subtitled ``The Show that Listens,'' and  
Dame Edna does that, too. It is part of Humphries' genius that he 
works his conversations with audience members into an important 
part of the act. The results are sublimely funny, as the Dame 
tweaks herself and her willing victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Dame Edna has no doubts about her status as housewife, megastar,  
icon and adviser to the Queen of England. She dispenses wisdom with 
maternal pride, talking with theatergoers about their clothes, 
eating habits, decorating ability and their children. 
</P>
<P>
	Edna also talks about her family: unmarried son Kenny, a fashion  
designer with a penchant for leather and head of the Yvonne DeCarlo 
Appreciation Society, and daughter Valmai, who lives in one of New 
York's outer boroughs with her same-sex partner, a former tennis 
star of Eastern European descent. Then there is Edna's mother, who 
is spending her remaining days in ``a maximum security twilight 
home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Humphries gleefully attacks the cult of celebrity while having  
his creation revel in it. Dame Edna has no doubt about her worth. 
She cheerfully and publicly corrects flaws in others, but ``only in 
the nicest way possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Audience participation is a dangerous game, but Humphries gets  
the most out of eager theatergoers, turning innocuous facts he 
learns about them into belly laughs. He even parades a couple on 
stage to eat a meal and dresses up others as members of the Royal 
Family. 
</P>
<P>
	For all the supposed spontaneity of the evening, the show is  
carefully constructed. Humphries operates loosely with that 
structure, but he thinks fast and furiously enough to insure the 
laughs don't stop. ``Dame Edna: The Royal Tour'' makes for mighty 
entertainment -- but then, the woman, of course, is invincible. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991017.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 12:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Martinez Shut Down Yankees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Pedro Martinez wasn't as unhittable as he was in  
his last outing against the New York Yankees -- or the rest of the 
season, for that matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he was merely dominating.  
</P>
<P>
	Missing as much as 9 mph off his fastball and still feeling the  
pain of a strained shoulder muscle, Martinez at 90 percent was good 
enough to shut down the Yankees in a ballyhooed matchup with Roger 
Clemens in Game 3 of the AL championship series. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the first inning, I had exactly what I had the whole game --  
nothing,'' he said Saturday night after Boston beat New York 13-1 
to narrow that gap in the best-of-7 series to 2-1. ``I didn't feel 
good at all. ... I didn't have a fastball. I didn't feel like I had 
a good breaking ball, or a good changeup at all. I just managed to 
spot the ball well, mix them in there and see what happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All the same, Martinez struck out 12 in seven innings, the most  
for a Red Sox pitcher in a postseason history, and extended his 
playoff shutout streak to 17 innings. He allowed just two hits, 
both singles, and did not allow a batter past first base. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, no runner has advanced to second in the last 14 1-3  
innings against Martinez, dating to the third inning of Game 1 of 
the first-round series against the Cleveland Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	In the fourth inning of that game, Martinez strained his  
shoulder. But that's only slowed him a little; Indians and Yankees 
hitters have just two hits in their last 45 at-bats against him, 
with five walks and 22 strikeouts. 
</P>
<P>
	It may not have been the 17-strikeout one-hitter he threw at the  
Yankees on Sept. 10, but it was plenty. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pedro proved what a good pitcher he is,'' said New York  
shortstop Derek Jeter, who singled in the first inning, then struck 
out twice against Martinez in Game 3. ``He didn't use his fastball 
as he has in the past. He beat us with his other two pitches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Martinez is unquestionably the Red Sox ace, with a  
league-leading 23-4 record, 2.07 ERA and 313 strikeouts, the 
37-year-old Clemens was merely the No. 3 pitcher in New York's 
postseason rotation. But with Clemens' history in Boston, where won 
three Cy Young Awards, Game 3 was trumpeted as a heavyweight 
championship fight. 
</P>
<P>
	But if it was, it was more like Mike Tyson vs. Peter McNeeley  
than Muhammad Ali against George Foreman: a quick knockout, with 
Clemens leaving after two innings. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-time Cy Young Award winner gave up a leadoff triple to  
Jose Offerman and went downhill from there. In all, Clemens allowed 
five runs while getting six outs to see his career postseason 
record fall to 2-3. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the injury, though, Martinez lived up to his billing.  
And that makes the Red Sox confident about another potential 
matchup between Martinez and Clemens in Game 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Now all they have to do is get there.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991017.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 19:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Arrives in Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAMASCUS, Syria, (AP) -- Former South African President Nelson  
Mandela and Syria's president exchanged compliments Sunday before 
meeting privately in Syria's capital, a presidential spokesman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Syrian President Hafez Assad praised Mandela as a freedom  
fighter respected around the world, while Mandela called Assad an 
``establishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I am happy to be with a renowned and a well-known president,''  
Mandela said of Assad after receiving a red-carpet welcome at the 
airport. 
</P>
<P>
	The two later met again for formal talks, Assad's spokesman,  
Jubran Kourieh, said. He did not give details. 
</P>
<P>
	Mandela, who is touring the Middle East and meeting with top  
politicians, was in Iran earlier Sunday. He planned to go to 
Jordan, the Palestinian territories and Israel on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mandela's visit to Israel was seen as a sign of reconciliation  
between the Jewish state and South Africa's anti-apartheid 
movement, which Mandela once led from a prison cell. 
</P>
<P>
	A sought-after mediator of international problems, Mandela was  
expected to encourage the Israeli-Palestinian peace process, the 
Sunday Independent reported in Johannesburg. 
</P>
<P>
	Mandela and other anti-apartheid leaders have said they shared  
the Palestinians' longing for self-determination, and noted that 
Israel helped supply military training, assault rifles and patrol 
boats to the apartheid regime. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tehran, Iran's capital, Mandela laid a wreath on the tomb of  
the late Ayatollah Khomeini, according to the official Islamic 
Republic News Agency, monitored in Dubai, United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
<P>
	Mandela praised Iran's severing of relations with South Africa's  
former apartheid government, and said ``we are indebted to the 
Islamic revolution,'' the news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Mandela also met with President Mohammad Khatami and Ayatollah  
Ali Khamenei, Iran's powerful spiritual leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Mandela recently brokered the end to U.N. sanctions against  
Libya, which were imposed because of suspected Libyan involvement 
in a 1988 bombing of a Pan Am jetliner that killed 270 people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991017.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 21:10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Creativity Seen in New GM Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WARREN, Mich. (AP) -- The ``Hi, I'm Jenny'' from General Motors  
Corp. offers weary city commuters a new place to park: the air. 
</P>
<P>
	Not available in stores anytime soon, the Jenny drives like a  
normal car. But when space gets tight, it takes to the skies and 
``parks'' by attaching to special hooks attached to office 
buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jetsons-esque vehicle exists only as a paper in the GM  
Portfolio Development Center, tacked to a wall covered with scores 
of ideas for new vehicles or gadgets. Like the vast majority, it's 
destined to be thrown away. 
</P>
<P>
	The wall is key to a new effort at the world's largest automaker  
to inject excitement into a stoic lineup of cars, trucks and sport 
utility vehicles, and catch whatever wave sweeps car buyers next -- 
before the competition catches it first. 
</P>
<P>
	``GM is a company that's in transition,'' said Wayne K. Cherry,  
GM vice president for design and portfolio development. ``For 
several years, there's been a focus on cost and quality. We're 
still focused on quality, (but) there's a renewed innovation in 
product and design.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GM has been occupied in the 1990s with keeping itself  
financially healthy, by battling unions, cutting costs and shedding 
entire parts of the company along thousands of jobs. At the same 
time, GM's place in the market has shrunk. In 1989, GM had almost 
34 percent of the market and sold 4.9 million vehicles. Last year, 
after strikes nearly shut down its North American production, the 
company sold about 300,000 fewer vehicles and had 29.4 percent of 
the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, competitors have won customers with more inventive  
cars and trucks, such as the Lincoln Navigator SUV, Dodge Viper and 
Volkswagen's New Beetle. 
</P>
<P>
	But with labor peace and lower costs in hand, GM appears ready  
to improve its lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	About four years ago, GM began working on a new approach it  
calls the Advanced Portfolio Concepts team. The first production 
vehicles to spring from its ideas will hit the market next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The team is a group of about 40 people who try to predict the  
future -- watching trends, interviewing sociologists and 
anthropologists and trying to answer all sorts of what-if questions 
about the world's future need for transportation. The group also 
looks to find ways GM can improve its cars or sell new products and 
to identify threats to GM's business, for example if gasoline 
prices soar or cities ban cars. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can have Scotty beam us over, we may not need to have  
cars and trucks anymore. We need to watch those technologies that 
affect how transportation operates,'' said L. Delf Dodge, director 
of portfolio concepts. 
</P>
<P>
	Teams of five to seven people then brainstorm about what kind of  
vehicles would be necessary for any combination of future trends. 
They condense those ideas into a ``inspiration board'' -- a 7-foot 
tall collage of photos, drawings and mottos used to keep track of 
the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	GM has about 360 ideas, including ``Hi, I'm Jenny,'' floating  
around the center. ``Dot Com'' is a vehicle that provides audio 
books and educational programs through GM's OnStar service; 
``Matlock'' is a car for older drivers with easy access and 
controls. Its not just cars and trucks; there are also ideas for a 
commuter train, video games, even power plants. 
</P>
<P>
	From there, the teams refine the concepts by trying to match  
them to a GM brand. To broaden its reach, GM has come up with 
themes that it uses to separate its brands; the portfolio designers 
have turned these into life-size comic-book character cutouts that 
they use as a visual guide. Saturn is a midriff-baring girl on a 
skateboard, while Cadillac is a sleek black robot reminiscent of 
the ``Transformers'' cartoons. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the ideas never move on to the next stage, where  
designers at GM's Corporate Brand Character Center fashion them 
into life-sized mockups and concept cars. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, GM will show off nine concept cars at major auto  
shows that have sprung from the portfolio center. One of them, the 
GMC Terradyne pickup, began as an idea called ``Work Truck'' aimed 
at men who need a utilitarian truck, said John Taylor, director of 
product design strategies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought, 'Well what about the bloke who really wants to do  
some work?''' Taylor said. ``He's been left behind here. He's 
forced to buy chrome and leather and 27 cupholders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The result? A beveled, brawny machine that can be hosed out, but  
also includes a fold-down laptop computer, an extendable pickup bed 
and hidden side bins. 
</P>
<P>
	Designers say the Terradyne is a fair indicator of what GMC  
trucks will look like in a few years. Features of the other concept 
cars could also eventually hit the street. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence Burns, GM's vice president for research, development  
and planning, said the company's goal is to have half of its 
vehicles be innovative, either by creating a new type of car or 
truck, or offering a new feature. 
</P>
<P>
	Burns said a few years ago, less than 5 percent of GM's  
offerings would have fit that definition. 
</P>
<P>
	``As Peter Drucker says, it's really impossible to predict the  
future,'' Burns said, citing the well-known management consultant. 
``You should spend your time creating it.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
