<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Senate Holds Off Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The balance between North and South was at  
risk and Henry Clay of Kentucky, standing on the Senate floor, 
waved in the air a piece of George Washington's coffin. 
</P>
<P>
	The fragment had come to him unexpectedly, as a gift. Clay said  
its sudden appearance was an omen, ``a warning voice, coming from 
the grave to the Congress, to beware, to pause, to reflect ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was ample reason for reflection in Washington in the  
winter, spring and steamy summer of 1850, 11 years before what some 
called ``the irrepressible conflict'' between slave states and free 
states would lead to secession and explode into civil war. 
</P>
<P>
	The recent victory of U.S. troops in Mexico, and the vast new  
lands that had fallen to the United States, had brought the law of 
unintended consequences into full play. 
</P>
<P>
	America had believed the North-South balance between free and  
slave states settled with the Missouri Compromise of 1820. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Mexican War had threatened the balance, bringing in new  
lands stretching from Texas to California. And the question was 
back on the table: Should new territories enter the Union with 
slavery or without? 
</P>
<P>
	The cockpit of debate was the Senate chamber where a gilt eagle,  
suspended over the presiding officer's dais, glared at senators in 
their curving rows of mahogany desks. 
</P>
<P>
	``All is now uproar, confusion, menace to the existence of the  
Union,'' Clay told them on Feb. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	In the long, nerve-grating debate, lasting until September, a  
Southern senator aimed a pistol at a blustering Northerner. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Webster, premier orator of the day, was battered by waves  
of abuse from Northern abolitionists angered by his bid to mollify 
the South. 
</P>
<P>
	And flinty South Carolinian John C. Calhoun, gaunt, feeble and  
in the final month of his life, would not be moved. 
</P>
<P>
	The Union could not be preserved, he said, unless the rights of  
the South and its slaveholders were guaranteed in ``honor and 
safety.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On March 7, 1850, Webster opened with words that were once  
memorized by America's schoolchildren: ``I wish to speak today, not 
as a Massachusetts man, nor as a Northern man, but as an American 
... I speak today for the preservation of the Union. Hear me for my 
cause.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate chamber was filled to capacity. Many senators had  
given their seats to women who attended the 3 1/2-hour oration as if 
it were a play. 
</P>
<P>
	Webster's underlying point: If the South was to give way on  
territorial issues its grievances must be addressed. 
</P>
<P>
	But he scornfully dismissed the idea that the Union could ever  
be disbanded peacefully, without the most savage of civil wars. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your eyes and mine are destined never to see that miracle!''  
Webster thundered. 
</P>
<P>
	Six days later, on March 13, Calhoun spoke in the Senate for  
what was to be the last time. 
</P>
<P>
	He had been misunderstood; his purpose was to save the Union,  
not destroy it, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But he saw the threat to its survival as coming not from the  
South but from the growing agitation of antislavery advocates in 
the North. He denounced Northern senators who echoed those views on 
the Senate floor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will not be on good terms with those who wish to cut my  
throat,'' Calhoun said. He died in his nearby boarding house on 
March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Clay made more than 70 speeches on behalf of an intricate  
compromise that, like the mechanism of a clock, would operate only 
if all of its parts were in place and in order. 
</P>
<P>
	Under its terms, California would join the Union as a free  
state; the debts of slaveholding Texas would be paid by the federal 
government; the territories of New Mexico and Utah would be 
organized with no encouragement to slavery; and, a strong Fugitive 
Slave Law would be enacted to return runaway slaves to bondage. 
</P>
<P>
	But the clockwork failed. The effort to pass an omnibus bill  
with so many working parts collapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	And then with Clay defeated, Calhoun dead and Webster in a new  
job as secretary of state, a fresh voice made itself heard. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Stephen A. Douglas of Illinois guessed that while there  
might not be a majority to pass Clay's compromise as a package 
there probably were majorities to approve each of its many parts. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as one section passed, Douglas brought up the next:  
Utah, Texas, California, New Mexico -- each territorial issue was 
finally settled,'' said Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., in an 
analysis written as a Senate speech in 1983. ``Just two weeks after 
Clay's omnibus bill had overturned, Douglas had hoisted it aright 
and enacted its various parts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, all that was won was time, important as that was.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on Congress, the  
White House and Washington's history for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
