<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sheppard's Son Ends 400-mile Walk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The son of Dr. Sam Sheppard completed a  
400-mile walk on Sunday that he started a month ago with the aim of 
preparing himself for trial of his wrongful imprisonment lawsuit 
against the state of Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Sheppard spent a decade in jail for the 1954 beating death  
of his wife, Marilyn, before a second jury acquitted him in a 
retrial. The sensational trial inspired a movie and ``The 
Fugitive'' television series. 
</P>
<P>
	His son, Sam Reese Sheppard, has been trying to clear his  
father's name and hold state officials responsible for what he 
calls a miscarriage of justice. 
</P>
<P>
	``Forty-five years ago today, tonight, my dad sat in jail in  
this county to go to trial tomorrow for his life,'' Sheppard said. 
``To go to trial in which the state of Ohio charged him with a 
capital crime and wanted to execute him. I believe that is an act 
of terrorism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheppard spoke from the steps of the Cuyahoga County Courthouse  
steps where he ended the journey he started Sept. 18 at the U.S. 
Supreme Court in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheppard had planned the walk months ago to coincide with the  
start of his trial. But the case was postponed from Monday to Jan. 
31 so county prosecutors could have time to analyze DNA samples 
from Mrs. Sheppard and the fetus she was carrying when she was 
killed. County Prosecutor William Mason had their bodies exhumed 
Oct. 5 to prepare for the civil trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``The walk was originally planned so I'd be here in Cleveland  
mentally and emotionally ready to go to trial,'' Sheppard said. 
``But the county prosecutors office decided to exhume my mother's 
body at the last minute. A last minute effort to delay the trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheppard, 7 when his mother was slain, contends the real killer  
was a man who washed the family's windows. He died while in prison 
for another murder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
